OREKA — Echoes of the Elemental Dawn
2
Chapter 1: Races of Oreka
The Kin are the mortal peoples of Oreka, created by the Elemental Lords and shaped by the Giants
and Elves during the earliest ages of the world. Their origins follow a divine sequence, each race
inheriting a fragment of the elemental powers that forged creation itself. From the towering
Giants who raised the first cities to the adaptable Humans who inherited a fractured world, the
Kin carry the memory of gods and cataclysm alike in their blood.
This chapter details every playable and notable race of Oreka, including their origin myths,
cultural practices, physical descriptions, inter-racial relations, and complete game statistics
compatible with the D&D 3.5 revised edition rules. Subraces are presented as distinct entries with
their own ability modifiers, spell-like abilities, and unique racial features.
The Order of Creation
The Elemental Lords shaped the Kin in a deliberate sequence, each successive race building upon
the lessons of the last. The order is remembered in every temple, woven into every Pasua ballad,
and carved into every Vestri hall:
The Firstborn: Giants. Stewards of creation, builders of the primordial cities, teachers of craft,
law, and magic. They harmonized the four elements and raised the first civilizations along the
Great River and in the Infinite Desert. Their era ended not in war but in a slow, stony fade, their
ancient bodies returning to the earth that made them.
The Secondborn: Elves. Shaped from divine breath and stone by the Youngest Brother, the Wind
Lord, within the great cities of the Giants. Born to be keepers of art, music, poetry, and dance,
they became guardians of wisdom and natural harmony across the forests and mountains of Oreka.
The Thirdborn: Dwarves. Carved from mountains and volcanic fire by the Lady of Fire in a
moment of solitude and yearning. Enduring craftsmen and defenders of civilization's foundations,
the dwarves carry their creator's passion in every hammer-strike.
The Fourthborn: Halflings. Crafted by the Lady of the Sea from seafoam and sand in her playful
yearning for voices upon her waters. Small, resilient, and irrepressibly joyful, they became the
river-folk and coast-dwellers of Oreka.
The Fifthborn: Humans. Shaped from all four elements and gifted with adaptability above all
other traits. The youngest and most numerous of the Kin, humans inherited a world already
scarred by the Shattering and the Deceivers' War.
Giants — The Firstborn
"Enduring titans sculpted from stone and elemental breath, guardians of the world's first dawn."
Note: Giants are an extinct race and are not available as player

Chapter 1: Races of Oreka
3
characters. They are presented here because their legacy is woven into every culture, ruin, and
magical tradition in Oreka. Understanding the Giants is essential to understanding the world they
left behind.*
Origin & Mythology
The Giants were the Firstborn Kin, created directly by the Elemental Lords in a time when the
world was still molten, wild, and shifting. They were not born of a single elemental patron but of
all four acting in concert—the only race to bear the mark of every Lord equally. The
Lord of Stone provided the deep earth of their bones, the Lady of Fire contributed the molten
heart that drove them, the Lady of the Sea gave them flowing memory and patience, and the
Youngest Brother breathed divine life into their lungs.
The Giants were made to be stewards of creation itself: builders of the primordial cities, teachers
of craft, law, and magic, and harmonizers of the four elements. They were not rulers in any
tyrannical sense but caretakers—beings whose immense power was matched by an equally
immense sense of responsibility. Their purpose was to prepare the world for the Kin who would
come after them, and in this task they succeeded magnificently before their long, quiet fade.
They crafted the first cities along the Great River and in the Infinite Desert, raised the great
runic forges that younger races would later inherit, and carved the first elemental circles—stone
rings imbued with stabilizing magic that still function today, millennia after their creators
crumbled to dust. Each city was governed by a Stone Council, elder giants whose mastery of
craft or elemental lore granted them rightful authority over their people.
History & The Fading
The Giants' greatest tragedy was built into their design. They were made unchanging—immortal in
the sense that they did not age as other Kin do, but mortal in that they could not reproduce. No
new Giants were ever born after the initial creation. The Elemental Lords, in their wisdom or
perhaps their oversight, had fashioned a race of singular purpose: to build the world and then step
aside.
For millennia this was not a crisis. The Giants lived for ages beyond counting, their stone-textured
skin deepening into cracks and fissures as centuries passed but their strength remaining. They
guided the newly created Elves with patience and affection, taught the Dwarves the secrets of the
forge, marveled at the Halflings' irrepressible joy, and welcomed Humans—the last and most
adaptable of the Kin—with a mixture of pride and melancholy, knowing that these youngest
children would inherit the world the Giants had shaped.
But eventually, inevitably, the oldest among them began to fail. Their bodies, having endured since
the world's dawn, grew brittle. Stone-skin cracked. Eyes dimmed. And one by one, the first Giants
crumbled into dust, returning to the earth that had made them in a process the Elves called
Thalorien—the "stone's sleep." There was no disease, no war, no cataclysm. The Giants simply
ended, as a fire burns down to embers and then to ash.
Their ruins now fill the Infinite Desert, haunted by Sand Wraiths—spectral echoes of the Giants'
final thoughts, trapped in the stone they once shaped. The Giant's Teeth mountains bear their
architectural legacy: massive, elemental-infused structures of stone and wood, weathered but
enduring, now claimed by dwarves, humans, or the wild. The Northern Lament Range takes its

OREKA — Echoes of the Elemental Dawn
4
very name from the grief the younger Kin expressed when the last Giant fell.
Society & Culture
Giant society was stoic, communal, and focused entirely on stewardship. They built grand cities
using their elemental magic to sustain life even in the harshest environments—the oasis-cities of
the Infinite Desert were watered by underground channels shaped by move earth and stabilized by
rune-circles that still resist the desert's encroachment. Their culture emphasized the sharing of
knowledge above all other values; Giants like Tharok, the greatest of their leaders, mentored
younger races in environmental care, elemental lore, and the moral responsibilities of power.
Art and architecture were inseparable in Giant culture. Every wall was a relief mural, every bridge
a feat of aesthetic engineering, every temple a working instrument of elemental harmony. Their
governance was council-based, decisions reached through deliberation that could last decades—a
pace that suited an immortal people but that sometimes frustrated the faster-lived Kin they
advised.
The Giants were benevolent guardians to all Kin, fostering alliances with Elves as advisors,
Dwarves as fellow builders, Halflings as delightful companions, and Humans as their ultimate
successors. Their patience earned universal respect, though their aloofness—a natural
consequence of operating on timescales measured in millennia—sometimes created distance. After
the Fading, their ruins became sites of pilgrimage, scholarship, and occasionally danger, as Sand
Wraiths do not always distinguish between reverent visitors and grave-robbers.
Religion & Magic
Giants were directly devoted to the Elemental Lords and their magic reflected this four-fold
bond. Where younger Kin typically align with one or two elements, Giants commanded all four
with equal facility. Their signature magics were stone shape (at will) and move earth (three times
per day)—powers of terrain manipulation that allowed them to reshape landscapes as casually as a
human sculptor shapes clay.
Their rituals left permanent marks on the land. The elemental circles scattered across
Oreka—stone rings that stabilize weather, suppress earthquakes, or purify water sources—are
Giant-made, and many remain active today despite the absence of their creators. Giant
rune-carving is the foundation upon which dwarven runecraft was built, and scholars believe that
even the Hasura's living-wood architecture descends from techniques the Giants used to grow
their desert oases.
Appearance
Giants stood 20 to 30 feet tall, with massive frames that resembled carved statues brought to
life. Their skin was stone-textured, ranging from pale gray to deep earthy brown, etched with
natural fissures that deepened with age. Their features were rugged and monumental—heavy
brows, broad jaws, deep-set eyes that glowed faintly with elemental hues: amber for those with
strongest fire affinity, blue for water, green for earth, and pale silver for air. Hair, when present,
was coarse and moss-like, often threaded with mineral deposits that gave it a metallic sheen.
Giant clothing blended Greek flowing robes with Assyrian geometric patterns—draped tunics
and layered kilts of woven hides or vine fibers, adorned with intricate friezes and elemental runes.

Chapter 1: Races of Oreka
5
Desert-dwelling Giants favored lightweight, heat-resistant fabrics in earthy tones with gold
accents, while mountain Giants wore heavier, stone-threaded garments. Accessories included
massive bronze or stone clasps and belts inscribed with protective sigils, many of which have been
recovered from ruins and now serve as treasured artifacts in dwarven and human collections.
