Elves — The Secondborn
"Children of the Wind Lord, shaped from divine breath and enduring stone."
Elves are the Secondborn Kin of Oreka, shaped by the Youngest Brother—the Wind Lord—from
divine breath and the substance of stone within the towering halls of the Giants' primordial cities.
Where the Giants embodied raw elemental power and steadfast endurance, the elves were made
to carry beauty, change, and meaning into the world. The Wind Lord, captivated by the wonder of
the Giants' creations, sought to craft beings of art, music, poetry, and dance—living vessels for the

OREKA — Echoes of the Elemental Dawn
6
world's capacity for grace.
This dual origin—air and earth, breath and stone—defines the elven peoples. They are creatures of
paradox: ephemeral in manner yet ancient in years, whimsical in temperament yet deeply rooted
in tradition, fragile in constitution yet possessing an inner resilience that has weathered every
catastrophe the world has known. Their connection to the Wind Lord grants them affinity for air
magic, illusion, and subtle spellcraft, while their stone-born heritage grants a cultural memory
stretching back to the Giants' first dawn.
Over millennia, as the forests grew and the world cooled from its elemental birth, the elves
dispersed from the Giants' cities and adapted to the landscapes they settled. Four major subraces
emerged, each embodying a different aspect of the Wind Lord's purpose: the Hasura, artists and
lightweavers who dwell in treetop cities; the Pasua, storytellers and charmers who gather in
circular forest villages; the Na'wasua, enigmatic stargazers who retreat to hidden groves; and the
Kovaka, stonebound warriors who guard the forests' edges where timber meets mountain.
Together, they form a mosaic of elven civilization, united by shared ancestry, the Elven tongue,
and reverence for the Wind Lord, yet distinct in culture, temperament, and magical tradition.
General Elven Physiology
All elves share certain physical and magical characteristics that set them apart from the other Kin.
They stand between five and six and a half feet tall, with slender, graceful builds that belie
surprising resilience. Their features are sharp and fine-boned, their movements fluid and
unhurried. Elven ears taper to gentle points—less exaggerated than human tales suggest, but
unmistakable at close range.
Elves live between 300 and 700 years depending on subrace, maturing slowly and retaining an
ageless beauty well into their final decades. They do not sleep in the human sense but enter a
meditative trance for four hours each day, during which they review memories of their long lives
in a state the Hasura call elarion—the "wind's rest." This trait grants them immunity to magical
sleep effects and a quiet awareness even during rest.
All elves possess Low-Light Vision, allowing them to see twice as far as humans in conditions of
dim light. Their senses are keen, particularly hearing and visual perception, reflected in racial
bonuses to Listen and Search checks across all subraces. Centuries of bow-craft and
blade-training have bred familiarity with the traditional elven weapons into the race itself: every
elf, regardless of class, is proficient with the longsword, rapier, longbow, and shortbow.
Magically, elves carry a natural resonance with air and subtle forces. Wind magic, light illusion,
nature resonance, and ritual-based spellcraft come more easily to elven practitioners than to any
other Kin. This affinity is not merely cultural but physiological—elven blood carries a faint
elemental charge that Na'wasua seers can perceive as a pale shimmer under starlight.
Shared Elven Racial Traits
The following traits apply to all elven subraces unless a specific subrace entry states otherwise.
RACIAL TRAITS
