Elven Relations with Other Kin
Elven relations with the other peoples of Oreka are colored by the long shadow of the Deceivers'
War and the Shattering of Man. Before those cataclysms, elves maintained cordial ties with most
Kin, particularly the Halflings and the Pekakarlik river dwarves. The Shattering—when human
kingdoms fractured and turned inward—left a residue of mutual distrust between elves and
humans that persists in many communities to this day.
Among themselves, elven subraces maintain strong cultural bonds. The Hasura and Na'wasua
share the closest ties, the stargazers serving as mystic counselors to the lightweavers. Pasua
storytellers are welcome in every elven settlement, their songs and tales forming the living
connective tissue of pan-elven identity. The Kovaka, more isolated by temperament and
geography, are respected as protectors and valued as intermediaries with the dwarven peoples,
particularly the Vestri.
All elven subraces share a deep unease regarding the Dómnathar, whom they regard as an
existential corruption of the Kin's divine heritage. This wariness extends to Silentborn—the
unnatural hybrids created by Deceiver experimentation—though individual elves vary greatly in
their willingness to extend compassion to these tragic figures.
Hasura Elves
“Graceful illusionists who whisper to the living wood.”
The Hasura are the most numerous and culturally prominent of the elven subraces, and when
other Kin speak of "elves" without qualification, they most often mean the Hasura. They are
artisans, historians, and scholars devoted to preserving beauty, knowledge, and the cultural
heritage of the Kin. Their great cities—grown from living wood in the canopies of ancient
sky-oaks—are among the most breathtaking settlements in all of Oreka, their platforms and
vine-bridges swaying gently hundreds of feet above the forest floor.

OREKA — Echoes of the Elemental Dawn
8
Hasura civilization centers on the Great Forests, where their treetop cities of Tiravel and
Myruvane serve as twin beacons of elven culture. Tiravel, rebuilt from the ashes of old Hillmeet
after the Deceivers' War, is a testament to Hasura resilience—a city literally grown from the scars
of conquest. Myruvane, older and more secretive, houses the greatest archives of elven
song-memory on the continent. The Windweave Glade, a sacred clearing between the two cities,
serves as neutral ground for pan-elven councils and the great Starweave festival.
Society & Culture
Hasura society is organized around clan-based families led by lore-keepers—elder artisans and
scholars whose authority derives from wisdom, creative mastery, and depth of knowledge rather
than martial prowess or bloodline. Governance blends these elder councils with bardic leaders
who serve as living repositories of cultural memory, their songs encoding centuries of precedent,
treaty, and tradition.
The Hasura excel in weaving wind and light into tangible craft. Their wind-silk fabrics, spun
from gossamer produced by giant moths on rune-etched frames, are traded across Oreka and
prized for their impossible lightness and faint luminescent shimmer. Illusory light
sculptures—temporary artworks of shaped radiance that tell stories or commemorate events—are
considered the highest form of Hasura creative expression. Bioluminescent moss art adorns every
public space, casting their cities in a perpetual soft glow that shifts with the seasons.
Festivals hold deep significance. The Starweave celebration unites all four elven subraces in a
gathering of music, craft, and starlit ritual at the Windweave Glade. Smaller seasonal festivals
mark the solstices and the first blooming of sky-orchids, occasions for the Hasura to renew their
commitment to beauty and to the Wind Lord's vision.
The Hasura maintain strong alliances with Halflings, with whom they share a love of storytelling
and river-trade, and with the Pekakarlik dwarves, whose engineering artistry the Hasura deeply
admire. Relations with humans remain strained in the aftermath of the Shattering, though
individual Hasura settlements—particularly Liraveth, with its mixed population—have made
significant progress toward reconciliation. The Hasura distrust the Taraf-Imro humans most
sharply, viewing their fiery ambition as dangerously reminiscent of the forces that brought the
Deceivers.
Appearance
Hasura Elves are lithe and fine-featured, standing 5 to 6 feet tall with builds that favor grace over
strength. Their most distinctive feature is their silvery hair, which ranges from pale platinum to a
deeper pewter-silver depending on lineage, often worn long and unbound or woven with living
vine threads. Their sky-blue eyes reflect their airy origin and seem to catch light even in
shadow—a quality that has inspired countless human poets and more than a few inaccurate
legends about elves glowing in the dark.
Many Hasura bear faint luminescent ritual tattoos acquired during coming-of-age ceremonies,
patterns of spiraling wind-motifs that glow softly under starlight or when the bearer channels
magic. Their clothing favors flowing wind-silk robes in forest hues—greens, silvers, and pale
sky-blues—often infused with light-enhancing threads that cause the fabric to shimmer faintly with
movement.

Chapter 1: Races of Oreka
9
Hasura age slowly, retaining an ageless beauty through centuries of life. In their final decades,
their features take on a translucent quality, their skin becoming almost luminous before they
finally pass. The Hasura call this last stage Lanariel—the "fading light."
Religion & Magic
The Hasura are devoted to the Wind Lord, the Youngest Brother among the Elemental Lords,
whom they revere as both creator and patron. Their spiritual practice centers on nature's harmony
and stellar guidance, expressed through rituals of starlit dance, wind-song, and the cultivation of
living spaces that blur the boundary between architecture and wilderness.
Hasura magic leans heavily toward air and light. Their illusionists are renowned across Oreka,
and even non-spellcasting Hasura possess an innate ability to conjure dancing lights—a racial gift
that manifests in childhood and serves as both practical tool and artistic medium. More
accomplished practitioners wield gust of wind, silent image, and the subtle light-shaping art the
Hasura call Lightweave, a tradition so deeply embedded in their culture that it has become a racial
trait.
Hasura temples are not buildings but living groves, shaped over centuries into cathedral-like
spaces of interwoven branches and filtered light. Their priests serve equally as artists, counselors,
and keepers of memory, and see no distinction between aesthetic beauty and spiritual practice.
Homelands
The Great Forests are the heart of Hasura civilization, hosting their treetop cities and sacred
groves. Tiravel, the largest Hasura settlement, rises from a grove of ancient sky-oaks at the
forest's eastern edge, its living-wood platforms connected by vine-bridges and wind-silk walkways.
Myruvane lies deeper in the forest, shrouded in permanent mist and accessible only through
paths known to the Hasura and their Na'wasua kin. The Windweave Glade occupies neutral
ground between the two, featuring open sky above and moss-carpeted earth below, ringed by
sky-oaks carved with the names of every elf who has attended the Starweave festival.
Hasura architecture is organic and airy—platforms grown from living wood, looms set on swaying
branches, and bio-lumen-lit pathways that pulse gently with the rhythm of the trees' sap-flow.
Their settlements are designed to leave no permanent scar on the forest, a principle the Hasura
consider both spiritual obligation and aesthetic imperative.
Hasura Adventurers
Hasura who take up the adventuring life are most often mages, rangers, or bards driven by a
desire to preserve beauty in a world still scarred by the Deceivers' War. Many seek lost artifacts of
the Giants' era, fragments of pre-Shattering knowledge, or simply the raw material of experience
that fuels Hasura creative tradition. A Hasura adventurer might quest equally for a lost wind-silk
weaving technique or a forgotten battlefield where fallen kin deserve proper memorial.
Favored Classes: Wizard, Ranger, Bard. Hasura make excellent illusionists and enchanters,
leveraging their innate light magic and keen intellect. Those who follow the ranger's path often
serve as far-ranging scouts and cultural ambassadors, representing elven interests in distant

