Pasua Elves
“Whimsical storytellers dancing with the wind's melody.”
If the Hasura are the mind of the elven peoples, the Pasua are their heart. Joyful, curious, and
irrepressibly social, the Pasua embody the Wind Lord's love of spontaneity and delight. They are
the storytellers, musicians, and charmers of the Kin—the race that remembers not through
archives and carved stone, but through song, dance, and the living breath of oral tradition. Where
a Hasura scholar might preserve a treaty in illuminated manuscript, a Pasua bard encodes it in a
melody that her grandchildren will sing without knowing they carry the weight of law.

Chapter 1: Races of Oreka
11
Pasua villages are distinctive even at a distance: circular clearings in the Great Forests, ringed
by vine-wrapped performance stages and decorated with wind-chimes that turn every breeze into
music. Their settlements near Myruvane and the Windweave Glade serve as gathering points for
traveling storytellers, and a Pasua village in festival season is one of the most welcoming places in
all of Oreka—open fires, shared food, and the expectation that every visitor has a tale to trade.
Society & Culture
Pasua society revolves around clan-based families led by bardic elders—singers, musicians, and
tale-keepers whose authority derives from the breadth and accuracy of their repertoire.
Governance is communal and informal, decisions reached through discussion that often resembles
a call-and-response song more than a formal debate. The Pasua distrust rigid hierarchies and
avoid the structured councils that characterize Hasura or Kovaka governance, preferring instead a
fluid leadership that shifts with circumstance and need.
Their greatest cultural institution is the Bloomweave festival, a seasonal celebration of new
stories, new songs, and new bonds. During Bloomweave, Pasua from scattered villages gather to
share the tales accumulated since the last meeting, compete in musical and storytelling contests,
and arrange marriages. The festival is also the primary occasion for Pasua to interact with Halfling
communities, who are their closest allies among the non-elven Kin and enthusiastic participants in
Pasua revels.
The Pasua are intrigued by humans—particularly their short lives and rapid cultural evolution,
which the long-lived Pasua find both fascinating and poignant. This curiosity has made Pasua the
most likely elves to seek out human communities, though the shadow of the Shattering keeps even
the friendliest encounters tinged with caution. The Pasua find dwarven culture stifling and tend to
avoid extended contact with Vestri or Rarozhki settlements, though they maintain warm relations
with the more easygoing Pekakarlik.
Appearance
Pasua Elves share the general elven build—lithe, 5 to 6 feet tall—but their coloring sets them apart
from their kin. Where Hasura favor silver and sky-blue, the Pasua are warmly toned: coppery hair
ranging from bright auburn to deep bronze, and amber eyes that seem to glow with inner
warmth. Their features are lively and expressive, quick to smile, and their body language is open
and animated in a way that other elven subraces sometimes find undignified.
Many Pasua bear wind-tattoos—swirling patterns applied during dance rituals that trace the
paths of air currents across their skin. These are considered marks of artistic accomplishment
rather than spiritual devotion. Their clothing favors flowing, vine-woven garments in earthy
tones—browns, golds, and harvest oranges—often adorned with wind-chimes and feather accents
that make a Pasua's approach audible before they are visible.
Religion & Magic
Like all elves, the Pasua revere the Wind Lord, but their worship emphasizes his aspect as the
bringer of joy, change, and the unexpected. Pasua spirituality is expressed through
performance—a well-sung ballad is prayer, a perfectly executed dance is devotion, and the act of
making someone laugh is considered a small offering to the Wind Lord's spirit.

OREKA — Echoes of the Elemental Dawn
12
Pasua magic blends air and charm in equal measure. Their innate ability to cast charm person
reflects not manipulation but the Pasua belief that connection between beings is the Wind Lord's
highest gift. Their spellcasters favor enchantment and illusion schools, and Pasua bards are among
the most sought-after performers in Oreka, their songs carrying a subtle magical resonance that
lingers in the memory long after the music fades.
Homelands
The Great Forests host Pasua circular villages near Myruvane and the Windweave Glade, featuring
open, airy settlements with vine-framed stages and wind-chime decorations. Unlike the vertical
Hasura cities, Pasua villages are built at ground level, their circular layouts designed to create
natural amphitheaters where sound carries evenly from center to edge. Architecture is vibrant and
nature-integrated, with living vine walls that bloom seasonally and moss-carpeted gathering
spaces.
Pasua Adventurers
Pasua adventurers are driven by an insatiable hunger for new stories. They travel not for treasure
or glory but for experience—the raw material that feeds their art. A Pasua bard might cross a
continent to hear a dying language spoken one last time, or join a war-band simply because the
clash of cultures promises tales worth preserving. They make natural party faces and negotiators,
their charm and social instincts smoothing encounters that might otherwise turn violent.
Favored Classes: Bard, Rogue. Pasua are natural enchanters and social operators, their racial
charisma bonus and charm magic complementing class features that rely on interpersonal skill.
Pasua rogues lean toward the charming trickster archetype rather than the skulking thief.
