Na'wasua Elves
“Mystical stargazers cloaked in twilight's veil.”
The Na'wasua are the rarest and most enigmatic of the elven subraces, dwelling in hidden groves
so deep in the Great Forests that even other elves speak of their settlements in hushed, uncertain
tones. They are mystics, seers, and diviners—elves who turned inward where their kin turned
outward, seeking truth not in art or story or battle but in the slow rotation of the stars and the
whispered patterns of fate.
Where the Hasura illuminate the world with dancing lights, the Na'wasua read its hidden currents.
Where the Pasua charm with warmth and laughter, the Na'wasua unsettle with violet-eyed stares
that seem to perceive more than the visible spectrum allows. They are counselors to the other
subraces—particularly the Hasura, who rely on Na'wasua foresight to guide their long-term
decisions—but they are not leaders. The Na'wasua prefer to advise, then withdraw, leaving the
burden of action to those better suited to it.
Society & Culture
Na'wasua society is clan-based like all elven cultures, but their clans are small and their
settlements deliberate in their isolation. Governance is guided by star-reading
councils—assemblies of elder mystics who interpret celestial patterns to determine the timing of
planting, travel, ritual, and war. Their most prominent leader in living memory is Aelthara
Starveil, a seer of extraordinary power whose predictions shaped elven strategy during the final
stages of the Deceivers' War.
The Na'wasua value wisdom, introspection, and foresight above all other virtues. Their culture is
contemplative to a degree that other elves sometimes mistake for coldness; in truth, the Na'wasua
simply operate on longer timescales than even the long-lived Hasura, weighing decisions against
patterns they perceive unfolding across decades or centuries. Their rituals are held under open
sky, preferably during celestial events—eclipses, meteor showers, and the rare alignment of
Oreka's moons.
The Na'wasua maintain their closest bond with the Hasura, whom they counsel on matters of
long-term significance. They trade cautiously with the Pasua, appreciating their storytelling but
finding their energy exhausting. Toward humans and dwarves, the Na'wasua maintain a careful

OREKA — Echoes of the Elemental Dawn
14
distance, wary of the Shattering's legacy and the Deceivers' War's fallout. Their isolation
preserves their mystic traditions but also makes them the least understood of the elven peoples.
Appearance
Na'wasua Elves are immediately distinguishable from their kin by their striking coloring. Their
skin is pale—not the ruddy fairness of northern humans but an almost translucent pallor, as
though moonlight has soaked into their flesh over generations of twilight living. Their
violet hair and violet eyes are unique among the Kin, a trait that Na'wasua tradition attributes to
prolonged exposure to starlight across millennia of nocturnal ritual. Their features are delicate
and otherworldly even by elven standards, and their expressions tend toward a calm, evaluating
stillness that many non-elves find unnerving.
Many Na'wasua bear star-shaped ritual markings—scarifications rather than tattoos, raised
patterns on the cheeks, brow, or hands that map personal constellations significant to the bearer's
birth or calling. Their clothing favors twilight-hued cloaks and robes of wind-silk and moss, often
embroidered with star patterns in thread that catches light from angles that shouldn't be possible.
Religion & Magic
The Na'wasua revere the Wind Lord through the lens of celestial harmony and twilight mystery.
Their spiritual practice focuses on reading the stars as expressions of the Wind Lord's ongoing
will—a living scripture written in light across the sky each night. Their temples are open-roofed
groves with quartz altars positioned to catch specific star-patterns at specific times of year.
Na'wasua magic is dominated by divination and illusion, with a secondary emphasis on
abjuration. Their innate ability to cast detect thoughts reflects a racial attunement to the unseen
currents of intention and emotion that flow between conscious beings. Their more powerful seers
practice clairvoyance, augury, and forms of star-based divination that have no direct parallel in
human magical tradition. The Na'wasua saying "You see everything better under stars" is both
literal and metaphorical—their Starlit Vision racial trait grants genuine perceptual enhancement
under open night sky.
Homelands
Na'wasua settlements are hidden groves near Tiravel and the Windweave Glade, shrouded in
permanent mist and warded by subtle illusions that redirect casual travelers. Their architecture is
ethereal and star-aligned—mist-shrouded sanctuaries with vine-draped canopies, quartz altars,
and viewing platforms positioned for optimal celestial observation. The groves feel timeless and
slightly otherworldly, as though the boundary between the material world and something deeper
has worn thin from centuries of ritual attention.
Na'wasua Adventurers
Na'wasua rarely adventure by choice. When they do, it is almost always because a star-reading has
revealed a convergence of fate that demands direct intervention—a threat too subtle for warriors,
a mystery too deep for scholars, a turning point that requires someone who can see the shape of

Chapter 1: Races of Oreka
15
what is coming. Na'wasua adventurers are quiet, watchful party members who contribute more
through insight and information than through direct combat, though their divination magic can be
devastatingly effective in the hands of a prepared caster.
Favored Classes: Cleric, Sorcerer. Na'wasua clerics serve the Wind Lord with a divination focus,
while their sorcerers manifest innate magical talent shaped by generations of star-ritual.
Na'wasua wizards, though rarer, tend toward the divination and illusion specializations.
Na'wasua Racial Traits
