Kovaka Elves
“Stoic warriors rooted in the earth's embrace.”
The Kovaka are the exception that proves every rule about elves. Where the other subraces are
graceful, the Kovaka are powerful. Where the others favor diplomacy, the Kovaka favor endurance.

OREKA — Echoes of the Elemental Dawn
16
Where the others build in living wood and wind-silk, the Kovaka carve in stone. They are the
stonebound warriors of the elven peoples—pragmatic, grounded, and forged for the defense of
their kin in a world that has repeatedly proven itself hostile to elven survival.
The Kovaka trace their origins to the borderlands where the Great Forests meet the Giant's
Teeth mountains, a transitional landscape of root-cracked stone, moss-draped cliffs, and ancient
caverns. This liminal geography shaped them into intermediaries: the elves who could speak to
dwarves, the wood-dwellers who understood stone, the people who stood at the forest's edge and
guarded it against whatever came down from the peaks or up from the lowlands.
During the Deceivers' War, the Kovaka bore a disproportionate share of the fighting. They served
as scouts, skirmishers, and rearguard fighters during the worst retreats, and their losses were
staggering. The war left a mark on Kovaka culture that has never fully healed: a grim practicality,
a readiness for violence, and a suspicion of outsiders that sets them apart from the warmer
dispositions of their elven kin.
Society & Culture
Kovaka society is martial and hierarchical by elven standards, organized around clans led by
Shieldmothers or Stonefathers—titles earned through demonstrated competence in warfare,
leadership, and endurance rather than inherited by blood. Disputes between clans are resolved
through feats of skill or endurance—wrestling matches, long-distance runs, or crafting
competitions—rather than through the deliberative councils favored by the Hasura.
Their values center on endurance, loyalty, and readiness. A Kovaka saying holds that "the
forest does not ask the stone to move; the stone simply stands." This ethos shapes everything from
their architecture—heavy, earth-integrated halls carved into cliff-faces and reinforced with runic
stonework—to their child-rearing practices, which emphasize physical resilience, self-sufficiency,
and combat training from an early age.
Among the elven subraces, the Kovaka are respected as protectors and valued as wartime allies,
though their dour temperament and martial focus can create friction during peacetime. They
maintain respectful ties with the Hasura and Pasua, admire Pekakarlik dwarven engineering, and
share a mutual regard with the Vestri dwarves that approaches genuine friendship—a rarity
between elven and dwarven peoples. The Kovaka are the elves most likely to engage with dwarven
culture, and Kovaka stonecraft shows clear dwarven influence.
Appearance
Kovaka Elves are taller and broader than other elven subraces, standing 5.5 to 6.5 feet with builds
that would not be out of place among lean human warriors. Their earth-toned hair—brown,
amber, and black—and green or emerald eyes reflect their affinity for stone and forest floor
rather than canopy and sky. Their features are strong-jawed and angular, marked by the
stone-like ritual scarifications that Kovaka warriors receive upon completing their first border
patrol.
Kovaka clothing is practical and durable: stone-threaded leathers and bark-steel armor dyed
in forest greens and grays, designed for concealment and protection rather than beauty. Their
rune-etched belts and moss-cloaks serve double duty as camouflage and identification, clan
markings woven subtly into patterns that only other Kovaka can read at a glance.

Chapter 1: Races of Oreka
17
Religion & Magic
The Kovaka revere the Wind Lord but with a strong secondary devotion to the Lord of Stone—a
dual allegiance that sets them apart from other elves and occasionally generates theological
tension with the more Wind-Lord-orthodox Hasura. Their spiritual beliefs center on the earth's
endurance and nature's balance, expressed through rituals of stone blessing and weapon
consecration.
Kovaka magic blends air and earth in a combination unique among elven traditions. Their
warriors augment weapons with earth-infused enchantments, their druids practice stone-meld
rituals that allow them to pass through cliff-faces, and their racial gift of stone shape reflects a
connection to the mineral world that no other elf subrace possesses. This earth-magic affinity is
what allows Kovaka to build in stone without losing their identity as elves—they shape rock as the
Hasura shape living wood, with an intimacy that dwarves recognize and respect.
Homelands
Kovaka settlements occupy the borderlands of the Great Forests, where timber gives way to the
Giant's Teeth foothills. Their stone-carved halls within the Windweave Glade's southeastern
reaches feature rugged, earth-integrated architecture: rune-etched walls, moss-covered roofs, and
fortified entrances designed to be defensible without sacrificing the elven aesthetic of harmony
with the natural world. The halls are cool, solid, and surprisingly beautiful—carved relief murals
depicting Kovaka history line every corridor, and crystalline skylights admit shafts of natural light
into even the deepest chambers.
Kovaka Adventurers
Kovaka adventure with purpose and grim determination. They do not seek tales or beauty or
cosmic truth—they seek threats, and they deal with them. A Kovaka adventurer is most likely a
scout sent to investigate a disturbance at the forest's edge, a warrior pursuing a Deceiver
remnant, or a young Stonefather-candidate earning reputation through deeds of strength and
endurance. They are reliable, tough party members who serve as the backbone of any group
fortunate enough to earn their loyalty.
Favored Classes: Fighter, Druid. Kovaka fighters are formidable front-line combatants whose
earth-magic augmentation and natural armor bonus make them more resilient than their elven
heritage might suggest. Kovaka druids combine earth and plant magic with martial training,
functioning as heavily armored nature-warriors.
