Dwarves — The Thirdborn
"Forged in fire, rooted in stone, unyielding as the mountains themselves."
Origin & Mythology
The Dwarves are the Thirdborn Kin, created after the Elves by the Lady of Fire in a moment of
solitude and yearning for companionship. Where the Giants had been shaped by all four Elemental
Lords in concert, and the Elves crafted by the Youngest Brother from breath and stone, the
dwarves were born of a single patron's fierce and lonely creativity. The Lady of Fire looked upon
the fading echoes of the Giant Kin—those magnificent beings already beginning their long
decline—and was moved to create something that would endure where the Giants could not. She
molded them from her brother the Lord of Stone's elemental form, infusing them with her own
breath and twisting their shapes with intense heat to forge their sturdy, compact builds.
The Lady of Fire imbued the dwarves with three gifts that would define their civilization: strength
to carve homes from living rock,
endurance to outlast any hardship, and a passion for craftsmanship that borders on the sacred.
Where elves create beauty for its own sake, dwarves create to last—their works are built to
survive centuries, and the best of them survive millennia. This drive is not mere stubbornness but

Chapter 1: Races of Oreka
19
a spiritual imperative, for dwarves believe that every well-made thing honors the Lady who made
them.
The earliest dwarves arose in three regions simultaneously: the Scorchspires, where volcanic
heat echoed the Lady's fire; the Giant's Teeth, where ancient stone awaited new hands; and
along the Great River's cliffs, where earth met water. From these three cradles emerged four
recognized cultures, each balancing the dwarven inheritance of fire and stone in different
proportions: the Vestri, keepers of ancient tradition; the Pekakarlik, river engineers and
boatwrights; the Rarozhki, volcanic fire-smiths; and the Aldenheim, bold forgers whose line ended
in heroic sacrifice during the Deceivers' War.
Shared Dwarven Physiology
All dwarves share certain physical characteristics that mark them as children of the Lady of Fire.
They are short and powerfully built, standing between 3 and 5 feet tall depending on subrace, with
broad shoulders, thick limbs, and a center of gravity so low that knocking a dwarf off his feet is
famously difficult. Their bones are denser than those of other Kin—dwarven skeletons, when found
in ancient ruins, are often mistaken for stone carvings because the mineral content is so high. This
density makes dwarves poor swimmers (the Pekakarlik excepted) but grants them remarkable
resistance to physical punishment.
Dwarven skin tends toward warm earth tones—ruddy, tawny, or in the case of the Pekakarlik, a
distinctive mossy green—and often bears a faint heat to the touch, a residual echo of the Lady's
forge-fire. Their hair grows thick and fast; both male and female dwarves can grow magnificent
beards, and many do, treating them as canvases for cultural expression through braiding, beading,
and ornamentation. Dwarven eyes are typically dark and deep-set, though the volcanic subraces
often display amber, gold, or ember-red irises that seem to glow in dim light.
All dwarves possess Darkvision out to 60 feet, an adaptation to their subterranean homes. They
mature at roughly the same rate as humans but live considerably longer—200 to 400 years is
typical—and their vitality remains remarkably constant throughout their lives, declining only in
the final decades. A dwarf of 350 can still swing a hammer with nearly the same force as one of 50,
a fact that contributes to the dwarven reputation for stubbornness: they have quite literally never
learned to slow down.
Dwarven Relations
Dwarven relations with the other Kin are shaped by two fundamental values: respect for craft
and loyalty to oaths. Races that honor these principles earn dwarven trust; those that do not earn
dwarven suspicion, which is extraordinarily difficult to shed once established. The Orean Humans
are the dwarves' closest allies outside their own kind, sharing a love of stone, tradition, and
mountain life that has produced centuries of fruitful trade and mutual defense. The Kovaka Elves,
with their earth affinity and warrior discipline, enjoy similar respect from the mountain dwarves.
Relations between the dwarven subraces themselves are complex. The Vestri and Rarozhki
maintain a warm rivalry—stone-craft versus fire-craft, tradition versus innovation—that
occasionally flares into genuine disagreement but is undergirded by deep mutual respect. Both
mountain subraces view the Pekakarlik with a mixture of bafflement and reluctant admiration; the
river dwarves' fluid, consensus-driven ways strike the mountain clans as "un-Dwarven," yet their
engineering achievements command grudging awe. The loss of the Aldenheim during the

OREKA — Echoes of the Elemental Dawn
20
Deceivers' War remains a wound that unites all dwarven peoples in shared grief and occasional
pilgrimage to the fallen city's ruins.
Post-Shattering, dwarven attitudes toward humans have grown more cautious. The fracturing of
the human kingdoms and the chaos that followed left many dwarven settlements vulnerable to
raids and broken trade agreements. The Taraf-Imro humans, who share the volcanic regions with
the Rarozhki, are viewed as forge-rivals and unpredictable neighbors. The Mytroan nomads are
simply avoided. Only the Eruskans and Oreans maintain strong positive ties with dwarven
communities, though the Halflings—particularly those who trade along Pekakarlik river
routes—are welcomed everywhere with the warmth reserved for pleasant but slightly eccentric
cousins.
Vestri Dwarves
“Stone-forged artisans rooted in ancient tradition.”
Lore & Culture
The Vestri are the most traditional and populous dwarven lineage, and they would want you to
know that—not out of vanity, but because tradition, to a Vestri, is the highest virtue. Originating in
the
Giant's Teeth mountains and the earliest mountain fortresses, the Vestri see themselves as the
cultural backbone of all dwarven civilization. They are the keepers of ancient stonecraft, the
guardians of stability runes that predate the Shattering, the engineers of defensive works that
have never been breached, and the custodians of council-based governance that other dwarven
subraces look to as a model even when they choose not to follow it.
Vestri dwarves hold themselves responsible for maintaining the cultural and spiritual memory of
the dwarven people. Their great archive-halls, carved deep into the Giant's Teeth, contain stone
tablets recording every significant event in dwarven history—births, deaths, battles, treaties, and
the specifications of every notable forge-work produced since the founding age. The Vestri believe
that what is recorded in stone endures forever, and they apply this principle with characteristic
thoroughness.
Society & Traditions
Vestri society is organized into clans governed by Stone Councils—assemblies of respected
elders chosen for their mastery of craft, lore, or leadership. Rank within a clan is earned through
demonstrated skill and service, not inherited; a Stone Council member's child carries no automatic
privilege, a fact that surprises human visitors accustomed to hereditary nobility. Disputes between
clans are settled through formal arbitration before a joint council, and the decisions reached are
recorded in stone and considered binding for all time.
The Vestri celebrate Stonefast, their greatest festival, which marks the annual renewal and
reforging of communal tools and weapons. During Stonefast, every Vestri settlement opens its
forges to the public, and master craftsmen demonstrate their techniques in competitions that draw
spectators from across the Giant's Teeth. The festival culminates in the Rune of Renewal, a

Chapter 1: Races of Oreka
21
collective ritual in which the settlement's protective wards are refreshed and strengthened. Vestri
dwarves maintain tight trade networks with Orean Humans, exchanging worked stone and metal
goods for agricultural products and timber.
Relations
The Vestri are natural allies of the Orean Humans, with whom they share both geography and
temperament. They respect the Kovaka Elves for their earth affinity and warrior discipline, and
they maintain a friendly but spirited rivalry with the Rarozhki, whom they regard as brilliant but
slightly reckless. The Pekakarlik are viewed as wayward kin—too fluid, too comfortable with
change—but the Vestri defend them fiercely against any outside threat. The Taraf-Imro humans
earn Vestri distrust for their volatile temperament and their uncomfortable proximity to the
Rarozhki forges.
Religion & Magic
The Vestri honor the Lady of Fire as their creator, but their daily devotion leans heavily toward
the Lord of Stone, whose patient, enduring nature more closely mirrors Vestri values. Their
magic emphasizes earth-binding spells, structural wards, and rune-craft focused on stability and
permanence. The signature Vestri spell-like ability is stone shape—the power to mold worked or
unworked stone as though it were clay—which Vestri artisans use in their craft as casually as a
human carpenter uses a chisel.
Homelands
The Giant's Teeth mountains are the Vestri heartland, where their fortified delves burrow deep
into ancient granite. The largest Vestri settlements are built into the mountain faces themselves,
with grand entrance halls carved to display the clan's finest stonework. Interior chambers are
warmed by geothermal vents and illuminated by phosphorescent minerals cultivated over
centuries. From the outside, a Vestri settlement looks like a natural cliff face with unusually
regular windows; from the inside, it is a cathedral of carved stone that can house thousands.
Appearance
Vestri Dwarves stand 3 to 4.5 feet tall with broad, sturdy bodies built for endurance. Their hair
comes in stone tones—gray, brown, black, and occasionally a pale quartz-white among the
eldest—worn long and braided with stone beads that denote clan affiliation and personal
achievements. Their eyes are typically brown or gray, steady and appraising. Vestri dress favors
heavy leather aprons over sturdy tunics, with rune-carved belts and boots reinforced with metal
plates. Even in formal settings, a Vestri dwarf looks ready to step into a workshop at a moment's
notice, because they usually are.
Adventurers
Vestri adventurers are typically driven by duty rather than wanderlust. A Stone Council might
dispatch a trusted clan-member to recover a stolen relic, investigate threats to a trade route, or
honor an ancient obligation to an allied settlement. Vestri fighters and clerics are the most
common adventuring classes, their defensive training and endurance making them natural
front-line protectors. Some Vestri develop a taste for the wider world and never fully return to the

OREKA — Echoes of the Elemental Dawn
22
mountain life, though they invariably carry a piece of home—a rune-stone, a clan bead, a flask of
forge-water—that they touch in quiet moments.
