Pekakarlik Dwarves
“Riverbound engineers shaped by water and stone.”
Lore & Culture
The Pekakarlik are the dwarves that other dwarves don't quite know what to do with. Born along
the Great River and the cliffs bordering the Infinite Desert, they absorbed the influence of the
Lady of the Sea alongside their fiery birthright, becoming something unique among
dwarven-kind: tunnel builders, boatwrights, and hydraulic engineers who are as comfortable on
water as their mountain cousins are beneath stone. The Pekakarlik view themselves as stewards of
the rivers, shaping safe trade routes and watery defenses with the same devotion that Vestri bring
to their mountain halls.

Chapter 1: Races of Oreka
23
Where mountain dwarves dig downward, Pekakarlik dig sideways—their cliffside settlements are
marvels of horizontal engineering, with tunnel networks that honeycomb the riverbanks and
emerge through hidden openings at the waterline. They pioneered rune-anchored architecture,
a technique that uses stabilizing runes to prevent erosion and cave-ins in the soft stone of river
cliffs, and their under-river tunnelworks—passages that run beneath the riverbed itself—are
considered impossible by engineers of other races who have not seen the Pekakarlik's water-ward
runes at work.
Society & Traditions
Pekakarlik society is smaller, more agile, and more egalitarian than the mountain clans. Their clan
elders are often Boatmasters or Flowkeepers—titles earned through demonstrated mastery of
river navigation or hydraulic engineering rather than age alone. Governance is by consensus
council, a practice that mountain dwarves find infuriatingly slow and the Pekakarlik find perfectly
natural: after all, a river cannot be bullied into changing course, and neither can a Pekakarlik
elder.
The Pekakarlik serve as neutral mediators between Elves and Humans in many river-trade
disputes, a role they have cultivated deliberately. Their greatest festival is the Tide-Turning, a
celebration of the river's seasonal flood that combines boat races, tunnel-diving competitions, and
communal feasts featuring river-caught fish prepared in styles borrowed from every culture the
Pekakarlik trade with. Their close alliance with Eruskan Humans and Halflings gives their
settlements a cosmopolitan flavor unusual for dwarven communities.
Relations
The Pekakarlik are the most diplomatically active of all dwarven subraces. They maintain deep ties
with Eruskan Humans and Halflings, with whom they share river-trade routes and a pragmatic,
community-minded outlook. They are friendly with the Pasua Elves, whose storytelling culture
delights the sociable Pekakarlik, and they respect the Hasura for their engineering artistry.
Relations with the Vestri and Rarozhki are cordial but strained—mountain dwarves view
Pekakarlik fluidity as un-Dwarven, while the Pekakarlik consider mountain stubbornness to be
self-defeating. The Taraf-Imro are avoided due to fire-water elemental conflicts that make trade
uncomfortable.
Religion & Magic
Pekakarlik worship blends devotion to the Lady of Fire with deep respect for the Lady of the
Sea, a dual patronage that scandalizes more orthodox dwarves. Their magic combines water
manipulation and tunnel-stabilizing wards—a practical fusion that allows them to build in
environments no other dwarf would attempt. Their signature spell-like ability is create water,
which Pekakarlik engineers use not only for drinking but as a diagnostic tool: the behavior of
conjured water reveals stress fractures in stone that the eye cannot detect.
Homelands
The Great River and the Infinite Desert cliffs host the Pekakarlik settlements:
tunnel-networked, rune-anchored warrens with boat-docks built into the cliff faces. From the river,
a Pekakarlik settlement looks like a series of natural caves with surprisingly well-maintained

OREKA — Echoes of the Elemental Dawn
24
wooden docks. Inside, the tunnels branch into workshops, living quarters, and vast storerooms
connected by water channels that serve as both transportation and climate control. The largest
Pekakarlik communities house several hundred families in cliff complexes that extend for miles
along the riverbank.
Appearance
Pekakarlik Dwarves are the smallest of their kind, standing 3 to 4 feet tall with slender builds
that would look almost elvish if not for the unmistakable dwarven breadth of shoulder. Their most
distinctive feature is their skin, which ranges from deep tan to mossy green—a unique
adaptation to their riverine environment that no other dwarven subrace shares. Their dark hair is
typically braided with river stones and small shells, and their large eyes—green, amber, or
brown—have a slightly luminous quality in dim light. Most remarkably, Pekakarlik possess
webbed fingers and toes, subtle membranes that enhance their swimming ability and mark them
as unmistakably river-born.
Pekakarlik clothing emphasizes water-resistant leather tunics and cloaks, often adorned with
river-stone beads and rune-etched belts. They favor muted greens, blues, and browns that blend
with the riverbank—a practical choice for a people who prefer not to be noticed by river predators
or hostile travelers.
Adventurers
Pekakarlik adventurers are driven by curiosity and commerce. A young Pekakarlik might take to
the road to establish a new trade route, investigate the source of river contamination, or simply
satisfy the wanderlust that their mountain cousins suppress but that river dwarves embrace
openly. Rogues, fighters, rangers, and clerics of the Lady of the Sea are the most common
adventuring classes. Pekakarlik excel in river survival, tunnel exploration, and diplomatic
situations where their natural mediating instinct proves invaluable.
