Rarozhki Dwarves
“Unyielding smiths forged in volcanic fire.”
Lore & Culture
The Rarozhki are the dwarves that other races tell stories about—and those stories usually involve
fire, stubbornness, and weapons of terrifying beauty. Shaped in the volcanic mountains by the
Lady of Fire's most direct and potent touch, the Rarozhki absorbed the flame's transformative
heat into their very being. They became masters of embersteel, the legendary alloy forged from
volcanic ore and quenched in elemental fire, and their smithing tradition is considered the finest in
all of Oreka—a claim that the Rarozhki state as fact rather than opinion, and that few who have
held a Rarozhki blade would dispute.
The Rarozhki's history is inseparable from their role during the Lament of Kings, when they
forged weapons for the Ascended God
Hareem's campaign of vengeance against the twelve kings who had betrayed the Kin. The blades
they created for that war are among the most storied artifacts in Oreka, and the Rarozhki have
never fully stepped out of Hareem's shadow. They remain a people defined by duty, honor, and the
conviction that creation itself is an act of worship.
Society & Traditions
Rarozhki society is organized around the forge, both literally and metaphorically. Their volcanic
holds are built around active lava vents that serve as communal forges, and each clan's forge is
considered a sacred space—a family legacy passed from Forgefather to
Forgefather, from Firemother to Firemother, across generations. Governance is by forge
council, where the heads of each clan's forge gather to make decisions that affect the hold.
Rarozhki disputes are settled at the anvil: the two parties each craft a work under the same time
constraints, and the forge council judges the results. This practice, called an anvil dispute, is
taken with deadly seriousness, and the loser is expected to accept the verdict without complaint.
Other important rituals include firewalk vows—oaths sworn while walking across beds of volcanic
stone—and flame offerings, in which a smith's finest work is deliberately destroyed in the forge

OREKA — Echoes of the Elemental Dawn
26
as a sacrifice to the Lady of Fire. The Rarozhki believe that nothing truly great can be held
forever; the willingness to give up one's best work proves mastery over attachment.
Relations
The Rarozhki maintain strong bonds with the Vestri, whom they regard as conservative but deeply
honorable—the two subraces have stood shoulder to shoulder in every major conflict since the
founding age. They admire Elven artistry, particularly the Hasura's lightweaving, which the
Rarozhki view as the air-element equivalent of their own fire-craft. Relations with the Taraf-Imro
Humans are the Rarozhki's most fraught external relationship: both peoples claim the volcanic
regions, both are fire-touched, and both consider themselves the Lady of Fire's truest children,
leading to a rivalry that occasionally erupts into open conflict.
The Pekakarlik are regarded with puzzled tolerance—the Rarozhki cannot understand why any
dwarf would choose water over fire, but they acknowledge the river dwarves' skill.
Post-Shattering, the Rarozhki have become increasingly isolationist, retreating into their volcanic
holds and trading primarily through Pekakarlik intermediaries. Their support for Hareem's
cause—forging the weapons of divine vengeance—has left a legacy of wariness among human
communities that the Rarozhki make no effort to dispel.
Religion & Magic
The Rarozhki are the most devout followers of the Lady of Fire among all the Kin. To them, the
forge is not merely a workshop but a divine space, and the act of creation—heating metal,
shaping it, quenching it in elemental water—is a ritual reenactment of the Lady's original creation
of the dwarven race. Rarozhki clerics tend volcanic shrines where eternal flames burn, fed by
magma channels that the dwarves have maintained since the founding age.
Their magic is fire-dominant and forge-focused. The signature Rarozhki spell-like ability is heat
metal—the power to cause metal objects to glow with searing heat—which Rarozhki smiths use in
their craft and warriors use with devastating tactical effect. Higher-level Rarozhki casters wield
flaming sphere and fire shield, and the most skilled among them can perform fire-bound
rune-craft, inscribing runes that store elemental fire for later release.
Homelands
The Scorchspires, Emberfangs, and Ashen Crown—a chain of volcanic mountains flanking the
Infinite Desert—are the Rarozhki homeland. Their greatest hold is Kharazhad, a fortress-forge
built into the caldera of a semi-active volcano, where the central forge is heated by a magma vent
that has burned continuously for over three thousand years. Rarozhki architecture is
unmistakable: fire-scarred stone halls with walls that radiate heat, ember-lit corridors, and
forge-chambers where the air shimmers with residual magic. The holds are uncomfortably hot for
non-Rarozhki visitors, a feature the Rarozhki consider a courtesy—they have made their homes
warm and welcoming, and it is not their fault that lesser races cannot appreciate the gesture.
Appearance
Rarozhki Dwarves stand 4 to 5 feet tall with compact, powerfully muscled builds that radiate a
palpable warmth. Their skin is ruddy, often bearing the faint, proud scars of forge-work—burns
and heat marks that Rarozhki display the way humans display medals. Their eyes are their most

Chapter 1: Races of Oreka
27
striking feature: ember-like irises in shades of red, amber, and gold that genuinely seem to glow
in dim light, a trait that unnerves members of other races and that the Rarozhki find quietly
amusing.
Rarozhki hair is typically soot-dark—black or deep charcoal—and often singed at the tips from
forge-work. Both men and women braid their beards and hair with metal beads of embersteel,
each bead representing a significant creation or achievement. A master smith's beard can hold
dozens of beads, making a musical clinking sound as they move. Their clothing emphasizes
heat-resistant leather aprons and kilts adorned with embersteel clasps and flame-etched
patterns, practical garments that double as light armor in the volcanic holds.
Adventurers
Rarozhki adventurers are typically driven by a quest for rare materials—unusual ores, elemental
essences, or lost techniques from the Aldenheim forges. Some are dispatched by their forge
councils to recover stolen embersteel weapons, which the Rarozhki consider sacred objects that
must not remain in unworthy hands. Fighters and clerics of the Lady of Fire are the most common
adventuring classes, though Rarozhki artificers and runesmiths (treated as wizards with a
fire-and-earth focus) are highly valued in any adventuring party for their ability to maintain,
repair, and enhance equipment in the field.
RACIAL TRAITS
