OREKA — Echoes of the Elemental Dawn
28
Aldenheim Dwarves (Extinct)
"The fallen firebloods of Aldenheim — bold forgers lost to the flames of valor."
Note: The Aldenheim are an extinct dwarven subrace, annihilated
during the Deceivers' War. They are not available as player characters. Their history is presented
here because the fall of Aldenheim is one of the defining events of Oreka's history, and their
legacy—in ruins, artifacts, and the grief of their surviving kin—shapes the world to this day.*
Origin & History
The Aldenheim were once the greatest fire-smiths of all the Kin, predating even the Rarozhki's
dominance of the volcanic mountains. They inhabited the Aldenheim city-state in the heart of
the Scorchspires, a fortress-forge of unmatched scale known for three marvels: their unrivaled
forgeworks, which could shape adamantine as easily as iron; their deep lore of fire elementals,
with whom they maintained binding pacts stretching back centuries; and the legendary Ember
Vault, a chamber said to contain a fragment of the Lady of Fire's original creative flame.
The Aldenheim were bold, inventive, and—fatally—overconfident. Where the Vestri counseled
caution and the Rarozhki valued discipline, the Aldenheim trusted in their own brilliance. This
confidence drove them to astonishing achievements: they developed fire elemental binding
techniques that other smiths considered impossible, and their weapons were so finely crafted that
some are believed to still be functional millennia after their creators' deaths. But it also isolated
them. Their boldness strained ties with the Pekakarlik and Vestri, who favored caution, and their
self-reliance meant that when the crisis came, they stood alone.
The Fall of Aldenheim
During the Deceivers' War, the Aldenheim city-state became ground zero for one of the
Deceivers' northern assaults. The Dómnathar forces struck the Scorchspires with overwhelming
power, targeting Aldenheim specifically—scholars believe they sought the Ember Vault and the
fire elemental binding techniques it contained. The Aldenheim refused to evacuate, choosing
instead to fight to the last.
They held for seven days and seven nights. The chronicles record that the Aldenheim
forgemasters turned their own forges into weapons, channeling magma flows against the invaders
and detonating stored elemental fire in devastating blasts that consumed Dómnathar soldiers by
the hundreds. But the Deceivers were numberless, and on the seventh night, the great forges
burst, the walls melted, and the city fell. The entire Aldenheim subrace was wiped out—every man,
woman, and child. Not a single survivor has ever been confirmed.
The fall of Aldenheim is mourned across all of Oreka, but most deeply by the Rarozhki, who
consider the Aldenheim their elder siblings in fire-craft, and the Vestri, who blame themselves for
not sending reinforcements in time. The Orean Humans, who received Aldenheim refugees during
the early days of the siege (before the city was fully encircled), honor the fallen dwarves with an
annual day of silence. The ruins of Aldenheim remain a sacred site—and a dangerous one, as
Dómnathar corruption lingers in the molten wreckage of the great forges.

Chapter 1: Races of Oreka
29
Society & Culture (Historical)
Aldenheim society revolved around the forge even more intensely than the Rarozhki. Their
governance was led by a council of forge-leaders, each representing a distinct discipline of
fire-craft: blade-smithing, armor-work, elemental binding, rune-inscription, and architectural
forging. The city itself was arranged in concentric rings around the central Ember Vault, with the
most prestigious forges closest to the sacred flame.
Their culture valued boldness, invention, and clan loyalty above all. Communal forging
sessions—where multiple smiths collaborated on a single masterwork—were their primary social
ritual, and fire rituals honoring the Lady of Fire punctuated every significant event from births to
funerals. The Aldenheim had little patience for diplomacy or caution, traits they dismissed as
symptoms of insufficient confidence in one's own abilities.
Appearance (Historical Records)
Historical accounts describe the Aldenheim as broader than the Vestri, standing 4 to 5 feet tall
with stout, powerful builds. Their most distinctive feature was their hair: fiery red or volcanic
black, never the stone-tones of the Vestri or the soot-dark shades of the Rarozhki. Their skin bore
ash-gray veins—thin lines of discoloration that traced their circulatory system, a unique trait
believed to result from their proximity to the Ember Vault's elemental energies. Their eyes were
deep-set and ember-bright, described in elven poetry as "coals that never cooled."
Aldenheim clothing was similar to Rarozhki garb—heat-resistant leather tunics and kilts—but
adorned with molten-metal clasps and flame-etched patterns of greater intricacy, reflecting
their more advanced forge techniques. Artifacts recovered from the ruins show workmanship of
extraordinary precision, with decorative elements that would require modern smiths weeks to
reproduce.
Aldenheim Statistics (Historic / NPC Reference Only)
The following statistics are provided for DM reference when designing encounters involving
Aldenheim ruins, artifacts, or undead echoes of the fallen city. These statistics are not available
for player character creation.
