Halflings — The Fourthborn
“Joyful wanderers born of seafoam and sand.”
Origin & Mythology
The Halflings are the Fourthborn Kin, and their creation story is the most charming in all of
Oreka's mythology. The Lady of the Sea—Lady Tempest, as the Halflings affectionately call
her—looked upon the world her siblings had filled with Giants, Elves, and Dwarves, and found it
wanting. Not in grandeur or craft or strength, but in joy. The Giants were magnificent but
melancholy; the Elves were graceful but already given to introspection and sorrow; the Dwarves
were stalwart but grim. The Lady of the Sea wanted voices on her waters, laughter along her
rivers, songs carried on her tides. So she scooped up a handful of seafoam and sand—the lightest
and most playful of her materials—and breathed life into them with all the delight she felt in her
own creation.
The result was a people perfectly suited to their maker's temperament: small, resilient,
irrepressibly optimistic, and possessed of a deep, instinctive bond with both water and land.
Where the Giants were built to endure eons and the Dwarves to outlast mountains, Halflings were
built to enjoy the moment—to find pleasure in a well-cooked meal, a story well told, a river running
clear, or a sunset viewed from the prow of a small boat. The Lady of the Sea did not design them to
be guardians or builders or warriors. She designed them to be happy, and in this purpose she
succeeded beyond all expectation.
Halflings arose along the Great River and the shores of the Kailian Sea, establishing themselves
in riverbank homes, coastal fishing villages, agricultural communities, and mixed settlements
alongside Pekakarlik Dwarves and Eruskan Humans. Their communities are among the oldest
continuous cultures in post-Giant history—not because Halflings are long-lived, but because their
settlements are so pleasant, so well-maintained, and so welcoming that no one has ever bothered
to destroy them. Even the Deceivers, during their terrible war, largely bypassed Halfling villages
in favor of more strategic targets, and the Halflings' neighbors fought all the harder to protect
communities that everyone—Elf, Dwarf, and Human alike—considered too precious to lose.
Halfling Physiology

Chapter 1: Races of Oreka
31
Halflings stand 2 to 3 feet tall, making them the smallest of the Kin by a considerable margin.
Their frames are compact but not fragile—Halflings are deceptively strong for their size, with
dense muscles and flexible joints that make them excellent climbers and swimmers. They lack the
bone density of dwarves or the lithe grace of elves, but they compensate with a springy,
irrepressible energy that allows them to keep pace with much larger companions on the trail, if
not in stride length.
Halfling skin is sun-kissed even in communities that see little direct sunlight, a warm
golden-brown tone that scholars attribute to the Lady of the Sea's sandy component. Their hair
grows in curly, earthy tones—browns, blacks, and occasionally a reddish chestnut—and is
typically worn loose or in practical styles that keep it out of the way while working. Their eyes are
their most expressive feature: bright and lively, in shades that seem to reflect the sky
itself—blue, gray, green, or a startling gold that catches the light.
Halflings mature quickly by Kin standards, reaching adulthood around 20 years, and live 100 to
150 years—longer than humans but shorter than dwarves or elves. They retain their youthful
energy remarkably well, with Halfling elders in their 130s still capable of the long walks, vigorous
cooking sessions, and spirited debates that define Halfling community life. A Halfling's feet are
notably large in proportion to their body, with tough, leathery soles that allow many Halflings to
go barefoot in all but the harshest terrain—a practice they consider both practical and
philosophically important, as it keeps them in contact with the earth and water their patron
goddess shaped them from.
Society & Traditions
Halfling society is built on a foundation so simple that larger races often underestimate its
sophistication: community comes first. Every Halfling village, from the smallest riverside
burrow-cluster to the bustling stilt-markets of the Kailian coast, operates on the principle that the
well-being of the group takes precedence over individual ambition. This is not enforced through
law or hierarchy but through a culture so deeply communal that selfishness is not punished so
much as pitied—a Halfling who hoards food or refuses to help a neighbor is not shunned but gently
drawn back into the fold, because the community genuinely believes that the hoarder must be
suffering to behave so unnaturally.
Governance is a loose council of storytellers and traders—Halflings who have demonstrated
wisdom through the tales they tell and the deals they make. There are no formal elections;
respected elders simply begin speaking with authority, and the community either listens or
doesn't, a system that works surprisingly well for a people who view rigid hierarchy with
instinctive suspicion. Major decisions are made at communal gatherings where everyone is
welcome to speak, and consensus is reached through discussion that can last hours, fueled by
excellent food and strong drink.
Halfling villages come in several styles depending on geography: riverbank burrow-homes of
reinforced clay and stone, coastal
stilt-houses that rise with the tide, boat-villages where entire families live aboard
interconnected barges, and inland orchard settlements surrounded by the meticulously tended
gardens that produce the legendary Halfling cuisine. All share common features: round doors and
windows (a cultural preference with no practical explanation that Halflings have ever been willing
to provide), communal kitchens, and a central gathering space where stories are told every

OREKA — Echoes of the Elemental Dawn
32
evening.
The Halflings' major traditions reflect their joyful, water-oriented culture. The Harvest Tide
Festival celebrates the river's seasonal bounty with feasting, dancing, and competitive cooking
that draws visitors from across the Kin. River Lantern Night sees thousands of floating lanterns
released onto the water to honor departed loved ones—a ceremony of such beauty that even the
reserved Na'wasua Elves have been known to attend. Songboating, in which entire families sing
in harmony as they row upstream against the current, is both a beloved pastime and a test of
endurance that Halfling youth use to prove their readiness for adulthood. And the Great Trade—a
decades-long pilgrimage in which Halfling merchants visit every major Kin settlement in Oreka—is
considered the highest achievement a Halfling trader can accomplish, earning the pilgrim the title
of Farwalker and permanent respect in any Halfling community.
Relations
Halflings are the most universally liked of all the Kin, a distinction they have earned through
centuries of reliable trade, excellent cooking, and a diplomatic instinct that borders on
supernatural. Their closest allies are the Pekakarlik Dwarves, with whom they share river
routes, trade goods, and a mutual appreciation for engineering ingenuity and communal values.
The two peoples have lived side by side along the Great River for so long that many Pekakarlik
settlements have Halfling quarters, and vice versa, with the boundaries between communities so
blurred that outsiders sometimes cannot tell where one ends and the other begins.
The Pasua Elves are the Halflings' favorite companions among the elven peoples—both races
share a love of music, storytelling, and celebration, and Pasua performers are welcome guests at
every Halfling festival. The Eruskan Humans are pragmatic trading partners with whom the
Halflings share a water-oriented culture and a merchant's instinct for fair dealing. The Hasura and
Kovaka Elves are respected but more distant—admired for their grace and strength but too serious
for Halfling tastes.
Halflings maintain a careful distance from the Vestri and Rarozhki Dwarves, whose mountain
stoicism and forge-intensity strike Halflings as admirable but exhausting. The Taraf-Imro
Humans are actively avoided—their fiery temperament and martial culture makes Halflings
nervous, and the feeling is mutual, as the Taraf-Imro consider Halflings frivolous. The Mytroan
nomads are viewed with curiosity rather than hostility; Halfling traders who encounter Mytroan
caravans on the plains report lively but confusing exchanges, as the two cultures' approaches to
hospitality differ so dramatically that neither is entirely sure whether they have been welcomed or
tolerated.
Religion & Magic
Halflings are devoted to the Lady of the Sea, whom they address with an intimacy that shocks
more formal worshippers. Where dwarves approach the Lady of Fire with reverent awe and elves
invoke the Wind Lord with poetic solemnity, Halflings talk to their goddess as though she were a
beloved grandmother—thanking her for good weather, asking her to calm the river before a
crossing, complaining when the fish aren't biting. Halfling theology holds that the Lady of the Sea
appreciates this familiarity, as she created them specifically because she wanted joyful company
rather than solemn worship.

Chapter 1: Races of Oreka
33
Alongside the Lady of the Sea, Halflings honor river spirits and ancestral community
spirits—the accumulated goodwill of generations of Halfling elders who are believed to linger
near their former homes, offering guidance and protection. Halfling shrines are simple affairs: a
decorated stone at the riverbank, a wreath of shells hung above a doorway, a small bowl of water
left on the windowsill during storms. The magic they wield reflects their patron's watery domain:
create water and fog cloud are the most common manifestations, used to aid navigation, protect
harvests from drought, and—in the hands of adventurous Halflings—create diversions and escape
routes.
Halfling spiritual practice also includes water blessings (rituals performed at dawn over rivers
and wells), protective charms woven from river-reeds and shells, weather-reading rituals that
allow experienced Halfling sailors to predict storms with uncanny accuracy, and luck rites—brief,
whispered prayers to the Lady of the Sea that Halflings perform before any significant endeavor.
Whether these luck rites actually work is a matter of scholarly debate; what is not debatable is
that Halflings are remarkably fortunate as a people, surviving catastrophes that have destroyed
larger and more powerful civilizations. The Halflings attribute this to their goddess's favor. Other
Kin attribute it to the Halflings' extraordinary adaptability and their talent for being somewhere
else when trouble arrives.
Homelands
Halfling settlements dot the riverbanks and coastlines of Oreka, concentrated along the Great
River and the shores of the Kailian Sea. Their villages are small by the standards of other
Kin—rarely more than a few hundred inhabitants—but densely packed with life, activity, and the
aromas of perpetual cooking. From the water, a Halfling village looks like a cheerful jumble of
round-doored burrow-homes, reed-roofed cottages, and wooden docks festooned with drying nets
and colorful pennants. The overall effect is of a place that has been lived in lovingly for a very long
time, which it usually has.
Halfling architecture emphasizes comfort over grandeur and resilience over display. Their
burrow-homes are partially underground, with thick walls of river-clay and stone that stay cool in
summer and warm in winter. Roofs are thatched with river-reeds or covered in living grass that
blooms with wildflowers in spring. Interior spaces are round and low-ceilinged—cozy for Halflings,
claustrophobic for taller visitors—with large kitchens, comfortable sleeping nooks, and at least one
room designated for storytelling and music. Every Halfling home, no matter how modest, has a
view of the water.
Appearance
Halflings stand 2 to 3 feet tall with compact, sun-kissed frames that radiate a lively, warm
energy. Their skin tones range from golden brown to deep olive, always carrying a warmth that
seems lit from within. Their curly hair comes in earthy tones—rich browns, deep blacks, and
occasionally a warm chestnut red—and is typically worn in practical but expressive styles adorned
with small shells, river-stone pins, or woven grass ties.
Their eyes are bright and expressive, in shades of sky-blue, storm-gray, leaf-green, or sunset
gold, and they convey emotion with an openness that other Kin find either refreshing or alarming
depending on temperament. Halfling clothing is lightweight and water-resistant: tunics and
cloaks in sea and earth hues—blues, greens, tans, and sand-whites—adorned with shell beads,

OREKA — Echoes of the Elemental Dawn
34
woven belts, and artisan jewelry crafted from riverstone, driftwood, and shells. Their feet are
large, tough-soled, and almost always bare, a cultural marker that Halflings defend with quiet
stubbornness against all attempts to civilize them into wearing boots.
Adventurers
Halfling adventurers are more common than their peaceful reputation would suggest. Their
communities actively encourage exploration—a Halfling who has traveled far and returned with
stories is celebrated, not pitied—and the trade routes that connect Halfling settlements to the
wider world naturally produce individuals who develop a taste for life beyond the burrow. Rogues,
rangers, bards, mariners, scouts, and water-attuned sorcerers are the most common Halfling
adventuring classes, reflecting a people who favor agility, cleverness, and social grace over brute
force.
A Halfling adventurer typically leaves home with three things: a sling (the Halfling weapon of
choice, wielded with startling accuracy), a recipe for their grandmother's signature dish (to be
shared with worthy companions), and a Farwalker's token—a small stone from their home river,
carried as a reminder that no matter how far they travel, the river always flows back to where it
started. Halfling adventurers form deep, cherished bonds with their companions and are
renowned for their loyalty, their cooking, and their infuriating tendency to survive situations that
should by all rights have killed them.
RACIAL TRAITS
