bonus on all saving
throws. (Stacks (Ex)
with Sea's Luck vs. fear for a total of +3.)
Weapon Prof. Proficient with all simple weapons and the sling. Halflings receive a +1 racial
bonus on attack rolls with thrown weapons and slings.
Sure-Footed (Ex) Halflings can move through natural difficult terrain (mud, shallow water, river
stones) at normal speed.

Chapter 1: Races of Oreka
35
Favored Class Rogue or Bard
Humans — The Fifthborn
"Adaptable heirs of a Giant's strength and an Elf's spark, fractured by their own potential."
Origin & Mythology
Humans are the youngest of the true Kin, and their creation story is unlike any other's—for they
were made not by an Elemental Lord but by two mortal beings who loved the world enough to try
to save it. Tharok, the last of the Giants, and Lirien, the first and greatest of the Elven
matriarchs, looked upon a land scarred by the Deceivers' War and saw a need that neither Giants
nor Elves could fill. The Giants were fading, their unchanging nature rendering them unable to
adapt to a world that had been violently transformed. The Elves, skilled and ancient, were too tied
to their own ways—too slow to change, too bound to tradition. What the world needed was
something new: a people who could adapt, who could thrive in any environment, who could inherit
the stewardship of Oreka and carry it forward into an uncertain future.
And so, in Tharok's research facility along the Great River, the Giant and the Elf conceived the
Fifth Kin. Tharok grounded them, pouring into the design his own endurance, his patience, his
strength—the qualities that had sustained the Giants through millennia. Lirien contributed
adaptability, the creative spark, the capacity for rapid growth and change that the Elves
themselves had always lacked. Lirien's sister Aeloria assisted with the delicate work of ensuring
the new race was viable, applying her knowledge of elemental biology to weave all four elements
into a single, flexible framework. Together, they launched four main ethnic lines, each attuned to a
core element and designed for a specific environment: Eruskan for the water regions,
Mytroan for the plains, Taraf-Imro for the volcanic zones, and
Orean for the mountains.
Lirien named the first successful human Eryndor—"Hope's Beginning" in the old tongue—and was
ecstatic at what they had achieved. Tharok, too, was proud, but he carried the knowledge that he
would not live to see his creation reach its potential. He poured everything he had left—his
remaining vital energy, the last reserves of Giant essence—into finalizing the human project. One
evening, he sat with Lirien and told him the work was sound, the future was in his hands. And
then, quietly, without battle or fanfare, the last Giant returned to the elements—his physical
form crumbling to sand like granite worn smooth by time. Lirien, heartbroken, raised a memorial
pillar at the site where Tharok fell. It still stands today, a place of pilgrimage and deep respect.
The Shattering of Man
For centuries, Tharok and Lirien's creation fulfilled every hope. Humans thrived, building cities,
trade routes, and complex societies with breathtaking speed. Their adaptability—the very quality
their creators had engineered most carefully—allowed them to flourish in every environment
Oreka offered, from the coastal ports of the Eruskans to the volcanic forges of the Taraf-Imro.
They formed the Eka Concordance, a loose union of the four subraces that governed through
cooperation and trade, and for a time it seemed that Tharok's quiet sacrifice had purchased a

OREKA — Echoes of the Elemental Dawn
36
golden age.
But adaptability, pushed to its extreme, becomes something darker: ambition without limit,
competition without restraint, change without wisdom. The water-based Eruskans clashed with
the fire-affiliated Taraf-Imro over control of shipping lanes and resource networks. The nomadic
Mytroans looked down on the settled Oreans' traditions, and the Oreans returned the contempt
with interest. Then an ambitious Taraf-Imro chieftain named Varkis obtained forbidden
technology—echoes of the Deceivers' own destructive arsenal—and attempted to seize control of
the Great River network by force. The result was cataclysm: earthquakes, floods, infrastructure
collapse, thousands dead.
Lirien tried to intervene, to mediate between the warring factions as Tharok would have done. He
lost his sister Aeloria in the process—she died protecting refugees during the worst of the
destruction, spending her own life to shield humans from the consequences of the very
adaptability she had helped engineer. The catastrophe fractured humanity into warring states and
shattered the Eka Concordance beyond repair. They call it the Shattering of Man now, and its
scars run through every human culture in Oreka: in the deep mistrust between subraces, in the
ruined cities that dot the landscape, in the lingering guilt of a people who know they destroyed
their own golden age. Lirien, ancient and grief-worn, retreated to the forests, where he still
dwells—never fully giving up hope that his creation might one day remember what it was built to
be.
Shared Human Physiology
Humans are the most physically diverse of the Kin, a direct consequence of the four-element
design their creators engineered. They range from 5 to 6.5 feet tall, with builds varying from the
lithe grace of the Eruskans to the stocky power of the Taraf-Imro. Their lifespans are the shortest
of any Kin—70 to 100 years—but they compensate with rapid maturation, high fertility, and a
generational turnover that allows their cultures to evolve at speeds that leave longer-lived races
bewildered. An elf who leaves a human city for fifty years may return to find it unrecognizable; this
is both humanity's greatest strength and its most unsettling quality.
All humans carry traces of all four elements in their blood, regardless of subrace—a consequence
of Tharok and Lirien's unified design. This elemental versatility manifests as a remarkable
capacity for magic of any school, a flexibility in class selection unmatched by other Kin, and the
signature human trait: a bonus feat at 1st level, reflecting the creative spark that Lirien wove
into their very essence. Humans learn faster, adapt more readily, and specialize more aggressively
than any other race, which is why they dominate Oreka's population despite being the youngest
Kin by a considerable margin.
Human Relations
Human relations with the other Kin are complicated by the Shattering and its aftermath. Before
that catastrophe, humans maintained cordial ties with nearly everyone—the adaptability Tharok
and Lirien had engineered made them natural diplomats and traders. After the Shattering, the
other Kin watched in dismay as the youngest race tore itself apart, and the resulting mistrust has
never fully healed. Elves in particular feel the wound keenly; the Hasura, who had welcomed
human scholars into their treetop cities, retreated into isolation, and Lirien's grief became the
grief of all elven-kind.

Chapter 1: Races of Oreka
37
Relations between the human subraces themselves are the most fraught in all of Oreka. The
Eruskan-Taraf-Imro rivalry is ancient and bitter, rooted in the resource wars that triggered the
Shattering. The Mytroan-Orean divide is less violent but equally deep, a clash between nomadic
freedom and rooted tradition that neither side shows any interest in resolving. Only shared
external threats—the Deceivers' War, occasional Warg incursions, or natural disasters—bring the
subraces together, and even then cooperation tends to dissolve the moment the crisis passes.
Individual humans, however, remain the most socially flexible of all the Kin. A human merchant
can be found in any market in Oreka; human adventurers join parties of every racial composition
without friction; and human settlers have established communities in territories claimed by every
other race. This irrepressible expansiveness is both admired and resented, depending on who is
doing the observing.
Eruskan Humans
“Fluid mariners guided by the sea's rhythm.”
Lore & Culture
The Eruskans are the water-children of humanity, infused by Tharok and Lirien with the Lady of
the Sea's watery essence and shaped for life along Oreka's rivers and coasts. They are navigators,
traders, diplomats, and boatwrights—a people whose civilization flows like the water that defines
them. Eruskan society centers on port cities like Velathenor and Rivertop, river towns strung
along the Great River like pearls on a cord, and maritime trade networks that connect distant
communities with a reliability that other Kin find frankly enviable.
Eruskan culture values adaptability, community, and clever negotiation above martial
prowess. Their reverence for water spirits runs deep, expressed through riverside festivals
featuring boat races, mist-summoning rituals, and communal feasts where the catch of the day is
prepared in styles borrowed from every culture the Eruskans trade with. Governance blends
elected mayors with merchant councils—a practical system that ensures commercial interests
and civic welfare remain aligned, or at least in productive tension.
Society & Traditions
Eruskan society thrives in tight-knit port communities led by cunning navigators and traders.
Families are large and interconnected, with extended clan networks spanning multiple cities
connected by river routes. The Eruskans excel in maritime skills, water magic, and commerce, and
they have developed a sophisticated system of trade law that other human subraces have
grudgingly adopted. Their riverside feasts and boat races draw visitors from across the Kin, and
their mist-summoning rituals—in which Eruskan water-mages call fog from the river to shroud
their celebrations in atmosphere—are considered one of Oreka's most beautiful traditions.
Relations
The Eruskans maintain strong ties with Pekakarlik Dwarves, with whom they share river routes
and a pragmatic, water-oriented worldview. They are friendly with Halflings, natural trading
partners whose communities often overlap with Eruskan settlements. Relations with Elves are

OREKA — Echoes of the Elemental Dawn
38
cordial but cautious—the Hasura once welcomed Eruskan scholars, but the Shattering left residual
mistrust. The Eruskan-Taraf-Imro rivalry is the bitterest inter-human conflict, rooted in
centuries of resource wars over shipping lanes, water rights, and the memory of Varkis's
cataclysm. Mytroans are viewed with suspicion, and Oreans with mild condescension—the
Eruskans consider mountain farming a less sophisticated pursuit than maritime trade.
Religion & Magic
Eruskans are devoted to the Lady of the Sea, whose watery domain mirrors their own culture's
values of flow, change, and community. Their magic emphasizes water manipulation: create water,
fog cloud, and mist-summoning rituals that enhance navigation and trade. Eruskan shrines are
built at the water's edge—stilted platforms over the river, decorated with shells, river-stones, and
offerings of fish—and their priests serve dual roles as spiritual guides and weather-readers, a
practical combination in a culture that depends on the river's cooperation.
Homelands
The Great River ports of Rivertop and Darnavar, and the
Kailian Sea shores of Velathenor and Lakeshore, are the Eruskan heartland. Their settlements
feature stilted docks, reed-roofed homes, water-spirit shrines, and the bustling markets where
river-trade goods change hands. Eruskan architecture is light and practical—built to withstand
flooding and easily repaired—with an emphasis on openness and airflow that contrasts sharply
with the sealed stone halls of the mountain peoples.
Appearance
Eruskans are lithe and graceful, standing 5.5 to 6 feet tall with the fluid movement of people
who spend their lives on boats. Their hair is dark—black or deep brown—and their most distinctive
feature is their sea-blue eyes, a striking shade that seems to shift between blue and gray like
light on water. Their features are weathered by wind and spray, giving even young Eruskans a
seasoned look. They favor
flowing, water-resistant tunics and cloaks in blues and greens, adorned with shell beads and
Riverstone Amulets—enchanted pendants that mark them as children of the river.
Adventurers
Eruskan adventurers are typically drawn from the merchant class—traders whose routes have
grown dangerous, navigators who've seen something strange upriver, or young Eruskans seeking
the wider world that their culture's cosmopolitan nature has taught them to crave. Rogues and
sorcerers are the most common adventuring classes, wielding water-based magic and riverine
cunning in equal measure. An Eruskan in an adventuring party serves as diplomat, scout,
and—when the situation calls for it—the one who talks the group out of trouble before swords
need to be drawn.
