Mytroan Humans
“Free spirits riding the plains' wild winds.”
Lore & Culture
The Mytroans are the wind-children of humanity, infused with the
Youngest Brother's airy essence and shaped for life on the open plains. They are horsemen,
scouts, caravaneers, and storytellers—a nomadic people who view the horizon not as a boundary
but as an invitation. Mytroan culture is built on movement: their tent cities and roaming caravans
follow the seasonal winds across the Stonewind Plains and the lands beyond the Infinite
Desert, never staying in one place long enough to put down the roots that Mytroans instinctively
distrust.
Mytroan values are shaped by the wind they follow: freedom, independence, and a deep disdain
for rigid tradition. Where the Oreans build stone walls and the Eruskans build harbors, the
Mytroans build nothing permanent at all—and they consider this not a limitation but a philosophy.
A Mytroan proverb holds that "the wind that stays in one place becomes stale," and this belief
permeates every aspect of their culture, from their fluid governance to their storytelling traditions
that change with each retelling.
Society & Traditions
Mytroan society is organized into loose family clans led by seasoned riders or
storytellers—individuals whose experience and wisdom have earned them the right to suggest a

OREKA — Echoes of the Elemental Dawn
40
direction, though never to command. Governance is fluid, guided by elder councils that form and
dissolve as circumstances require. Major decisions are made around campfires, where anyone may
speak and where the quality of one's argument matters more than one's age or lineage. Mytroans
excel in horsemanship, air magic, and survival skills honed by generations of plains living.
Their traditions revolve around movement and the open sky. Wind dances—rituals performed at
dawn where dancers trace the air currents with their bodies—honor the Youngest Brother and are
believed to bring favorable travel weather. Caravan races, in which rival clans compete to
navigate a set course across open terrain at speed, serve as both entertainment and a practical
test of the skills every Mytroan needs to survive. Storytelling is the Mytroans' highest art form;
their oral histories, recited from memory across generations, are considered some of the most
vivid and emotionally powerful narratives in all of Oreka.
Relations
Mytroans engage most readily with the Pasua Elves, whose storytelling culture and whimsical
nature echo the Mytroans' own love of narrative and freedom. They respect the Hasura for their
artistry and show distant curiosity toward the Na'wasua, whose mystical ways fascinate even the
pragmatic Mytroans. Relations with the Oreans are the Mytroans' bitterest inter-human conflict:
the nomads despise Orean traditionalism as a kind of spiritual death, while the Oreans view
Mytroan rootlessness as irresponsible and dangerous.
Mytroans avoid Dwarven communities almost entirely—the idea of living underground strikes
them as a horror—and view both the
Eruskans and the Taraf-Imro with post-Shattering suspicion. Their presence in North Central
Oreka is limited to visiting traders and relic-seekers who pass through the ruins of Mytro and
Hylen, once-great Mytroan settlements that fell during the Deceivers' War and have never been
reclaimed.
Religion & Magic
Mytroans are devoted to the Youngest Brother, the Wind Lord, whose domain of air, change, and
freedom perfectly mirrors their cultural values. Their magic emphasizes mobility and atmospheric
manipulation: gust of wind, feather fall, and wind-blessing rituals that enhance speed, lighten
burdens, and—in the hands of skilled Mytroan shamans—redirect storms away from caravan
routes. Mytroan shrines are portable—wind-flags and prayer-pennants carried on poles that snap
in the breeze—and their priests are wanderers who travel between clans, carrying news, settling
disputes, and performing the wind-blessing rituals that keep the caravans safe.
Homelands
The Stonewind Plains and the open lands beyond the Infinite Desert are the Mytroan
homeland—though "homeland" is a word that sits uneasily on a Mytroan tongue, since they define
home by the people they travel with rather than the ground beneath their feet. Their tent cities are
temporary marvels of portable engineering: wind-resistant hide shelters that can be assembled in
minutes and struck even faster, arranged in concentric circles around a central fire-pit where the
evening's stories are told. Mytroan camps leave almost no trace when they move on, a point of
pride for a people who believe the land should look the same after they leave as it did before they
arrived.

Chapter 1: Races of Oreka
41
Appearance
Mytroans are tall and wiry, standing 5.5 to 6.5 feet tall with the lean, wind-sculpted builds of
people who spend their lives in the saddle. Their hair is notably light—pale blond, ash-brown, or
silver-streaked—and often worn long and loose, whipping behind them as they ride. Their stormy
gray eyes are their most striking feature, a pale, shifting shade that seems to mirror the sky above
the plains. Their features are weathered by wind and sun, with high cheekbones and sharp
jawlines that give them a hawkish, alert appearance.
Mytroan clothing is designed for life on horseback: loose, wind-resistant robes and cloaks in
neutral tones—grays, tans, and dust-browns—layered for warmth and cinched with leather belts
hung with pouches, water-skins, and feather charms that mark clan affiliation and personal
achievements. Their boots are soft-soled for stirrup-work, and many Mytroans wear their
weapons—curved short-swords and composite bows—so naturally that the tools seem like
extensions of their bodies.
Adventurers
Mytroan adventurers need no excuse to take to the road—for them, the road is home. Rangers and
barbarians are the most common adventuring classes, their plains-honed survival skills and
mounted combat training translating seamlessly to a life of exploration. Mytroan bards are also
highly valued, their oral tradition producing storytellers of extraordinary power whose tales can
inspire courage, provoke tears, or—in the case of the most skilled—literally conjure the winds they
describe. A Mytroan in an adventuring party is the scout, the outrider, the one who sees trouble
coming across open ground before anyone else even knows to look.
