Orean Humans
“Steadfast builders rooted in the mountain's strength.”
Lore & Culture
The Oreans are the earth-children of humanity, infused with the Lord of Stone's enduring
essence and shaped for life in Oreka's mountain valleys. They are farmers, builders, stone-carvers,
and guardians—a people whose culture is as steady and immovable as the granite they build with.
Where the Eruskans flow and the Mytroans drift, the Oreans stay. They plant orchards, quarry
stone, raise walls, and defend what they've built with a stubbornness that rivals the

Chapter 1: Races of Oreka
45
dwarves—their closest allies and, in many ways, their cultural role models.
Orean values mirror the element that defines them: tradition, stability, craft, and community
protection. Change comes slowly to Orean settlements, and the Oreans like it that way. Their
stone villages have stood in the Giant's Teeth valleys for centuries, repaired and expanded but
never abandoned, and an Orean measuring the worth of a thing asks one question above all
others: will it last? This conservatism makes the Oreans reliable allies, excellent builders, and
maddening negotiating partners—an Orean who has made up his mind can no more be argued out
of his position than a mountain can be argued out of its valley.
Society & Traditions
Orean society is organized into tight-knit valley communities governed by elected elders and
advised by druidic councils whose members maintain the earth-magic traditions that keep the
mountain farms productive and the stone walls strong. Families are large, patriarchal or
matriarchal depending on the valley, and deeply rooted—an Orean can typically trace their lineage
back a dozen generations, and considers this a modest achievement compared to their dwarven
neighbors.
Orean traditions celebrate the earth and its gifts. Stone-carving contests, in which artisans
compete to produce the finest piece from a single block of valley granite, are the Orean equivalent
of the Taraf-Imro's forge-dances. Harvest feasts mark the end of the agricultural season with
communal meals, music, and the ritualistic
First Stone ceremony, in which the eldest elder places a new cornerstone on whatever building
project the community has planned for the coming year. The Oreans' bond with the Vestri
Dwarves is expressed through shared markets, joint construction projects, and an annual
exchange of master craftsmen that both peoples consider one of the most important traditions in
the Giant's Teeth.
Relations
The Oreans' closest allies are the Vestri Dwarves, with whom they share geography,
temperament, and a love of stone that transcends racial boundaries. The two peoples have traded,
built together, and defended each other's settlements for so long that the relationship feels less
like an alliance and more like an extended family. The Oreans respect the Kovaka Elves for their
warrior discipline and earth affinity, and they trade cautiously with the Eruskans, whose maritime
goods supplement the mountain communities' inland economy.
The Mytroans are the Oreans' bitterest rivals. The nomads' rootless ways offend everything the
Oreans believe about the importance of land, home, and permanence, and the Mytroans' contempt
for Orean tradition is returned with quiet, granite-hard intensity. The Taraf-Imro are
avoided—their volcanic ambition makes the cautious Oreans nervous—and even the Pekakarlik
Dwarves are viewed with mild suspicion, their river-dwelling ways too fluid for Orean comfort.
Post-Shattering, the Oreans have turned inward, focused on maintaining their own communities
rather than engaging with the wider world—a strategy that has served them well, if at the cost of
political influence beyond the mountains.
Religion & Magic

OREKA — Echoes of the Elemental Dawn
46
Oreans are devoted to the Lord of Stone, the Elemental Lord whose patient, enduring nature
most closely mirrors their own values. Their magic emphasizes earth manipulation: stone shape,
spike stones, and ritual wardings that strengthen foundations, protect crops from erosion, and—in
times of war—turn the mountain valleys into death-traps for invaders. Orean shrines are stone
circles built in high meadows, where druidic priests perform stone blessings at dawn and dusk,
ensuring the earth remains fertile and the foundations remain sound.
Homelands
The Giant's Teeth valleys and mountain regions host the Orean settlements: stone-built villages
nestled in sheltered valleys, surrounded by terraced farmland that climbs the mountainsides in
carefully maintained steps. Stonefall is the largest Orean community, a valley-spanning town of
granite halls and basalt-quarry workshops that serves as the informal capital of Orean culture. The
architecture is heavy, low, and built to endure—Orean buildings have walls thick enough to serve
as fortifications, a practical consideration in a region where mountain weather and occasional
Warg raids make sturdiness a survival trait.
Appearance
Oreans are broad and sturdy, standing 5.5 to 6.5 feet tall with the powerful, grounded builds of
people who work stone and till mountain soil. Their hair is dark—black or deep brown—typically
worn short and practical, and their earthy brown eyes have a steady, measuring quality that
makes visitors feel they are being appraised for load-bearing capacity. Their features are
weathered by mountain life: square jaws, broad noses, and skin that tans to a warm bronze in
summer and stays ruddy through winter.
Orean clothing is durable and earth-toned: heavy tunics and cloaks in browns, grays, and forest
greens, reinforced at the elbows and knees for manual labor. Rune-etched belts are the Oreans'
one concession to ornamentation—each family has a set of protective runes passed down through
generations, and wearing them is both a fashion statement and a spiritual practice. Stone beads
braided into hair or strung on leather cords mark clan affiliation, and Orean boots are legendary
for their durability, constructed by mountain cobblers whose craft rivals the dwarves'.
Adventurers
Orean adventurers are the rarest of the human subraces—a people who value staying put do not
produce many wanderers. Those who do take to the road are typically driven by necessity: a threat
to their valley that requires outside help, a quest to recover stolen relics, or a druidic vision that
compels a young Orean to leave the mountains and learn what the wider world has to teach.
Fighters and druids are the most common adventuring classes, their physical toughness and
earth-magic making them natural protectors and healers. An Orean in an adventuring party is the
anchor—the one who holds the line, carries the heaviest pack, and never, under any
circumstances, suggests that the group should give up and go home.
