Hybrid Peoples
Hybrid peoples arise where elemental bloodlines, ancient legacies, or unnatural experiments
blend the heritage of two or more races. In Oreka, three hybrid races hold major cultural and
historical significance: the Half-Giants, natural hybrids born of the twilight union between the
fading Giants and early Humans; the Silentborn, unnatural hybrids created through the
Dómnathar's brutal breeding experiments on captured Kin; and the Half-Dómnathar, mixed
offspring of Kin and Dómnathar infiltrators, born into conflict and suspicion. These peoples often
struggle to find belonging among their parent races, but their unique strengths—and their unique
suffering—have shaped the world in ways that no pure-blooded Kin could have achieved alone.
Half-Giants
“Titanic heirs bridging ancient might and mortal will.”
Origin & Mythology
Half-Giants emerged from rare unions between the fading Giants and early Humans during the
twilight of the Giants' era. They were not planned. They were not engineered. They were simply
what happened when two peoples—one ancient and dying, the other young and vital—lived close
enough together for long enough that love, or loneliness, or simple proximity did what love and
loneliness have always done. The first Half-Giants were born along the Great River during the
early human age, in the shadow of Tharok's memorial pillar, and from the moment of their birth
they occupied an impossible position: too human to be Giants, too Giant to be human, and too
valuable to be ignored by either.

OREKA — Echoes of the Elemental Dawn
48
Half-Giants carry the endurance and elemental memory of the Giants blended with the
adaptability and ambition of Humans. They are living relics of the ancient world, walking
reminders that the Firstborn are not entirely gone. The elemental resonance that once sustained
the Giants lingers in their blood—muted, fragmented, but unmistakably present—and this residual
power grants them a connection to the earth and to elemental magic that no pure-blooded human
can match. Among the Kin, they are regarded with a complicated mixture of awe, pity, and unease:
awe for the Giant heritage they embody, pity for the loneliness of their position, and unease at the
reminder that even the mightiest civilizations can dwindle to half-remembered echoes in the blood
of their descendants.
Society & Traditions
Half-Giants do not have nations of their own. Their numbers have never been large enough, and
their temperaments are too varied, for them to form the kind of cohesive communities that other
races take for granted. Instead, they integrate into Human or Dwarven communities, where
their enormous strength and elemental affinity make them valued laborers, guardians, mediators,
and rune-workers. Some form small family clans—loose groupings of two or three Half-Giant
families who travel together and share traditions—but these clans are rare and widely scattered.
Half-Giant traditions center on honoring their Giant ancestry while accepting their human present.
Stone rituals—ceremonies in which Half-Giants carve runes into river-stones and leave them at
places of significance—are their most distinctive cultural practice, a scaled-down echo of the
Giants' own monumental stone-shaping. Communal storytelling preserves the fragments of
Giant history that Half-Giants have inherited, and feats of endurance—contests of strength,
stamina, and patience—serve as both entertainment and spiritual practice, connecting
participants to the patient, enduring nature of the Firstborn.
Relations
Half-Giants maintain strong ties with Orean Humans and Vestri Dwarves, peoples whose
earth-oriented cultures and respect for tradition mirror the Half-Giants' own values. The Kovaka
Elves respect Half-Giants for their shared earth affinity, and the
Pekakarlik Dwarves trade with them readily. Relations with the
Mytroans and Taraf-Imro are more strained—the nomads find Half-Giants unsettling, and the
fire-touched humans view their size and elemental power as a potential threat. Among the Kin at
large, Half-Giants are treated with a cautious respect that sometimes shades into reverence,
particularly in Orean communities, where the memory of the Giants is honored as sacred history.
Religion & Magic
Half-Giants primarily honor the Lord of Stone, whose patient, enduring nature resonates most
deeply with their Giant heritage. They also acknowledge the Lady of Fire, the Lady of the Sea, and
the Youngest Brother, reflecting the all-element spark that Tharok and Lirien wove into humanity.
Their magic is earth-focused but versatile: stone shape and produce flame are the most common
manifestations, alongside rune-guided earthshaping—a slower, more deliberate form of
elemental magic that Half-Giants practice as both craft and meditation. A Half-Giant shaping stone
through rune-work is one of the most mesmerizing sights in Oreka—the massive hands moving
with delicate precision, coaxing rock into forms that seem to grow rather than be carved.

Chapter 1: Races of Oreka
49
Appearance
Half-Giants stand 8 to 12 feet tall, towering over every other playable race in Oreka. Their builds
are massively muscular, with the broad shoulders and thick limbs of people built to move
mountains—which, in the case of their Giant ancestors, was sometimes literally true. Their most
striking feature is their stone-textured skin, a rough, mineral-flecked surface in shades of
granite gray, sandstone gold, or basalt black that catches the light like polished rock. Their eyes
carry an elemental tint—amber, deep brown, or a warm, glowing earth-tone that seems to flicker
in firelight.
Half-Giant fashion reflects both their heritages. They favor Greek and Assyrian-blended
garments—draped tunics, broad belts, and sandals—that echo the ancient Giant aesthetic
preserved in the ruins of the Infinite Desert, combined with practical elements borrowed from
whichever human or dwarven culture they've integrated into. Many Half-Giants wear stone
jewelry carved by their own hands: amulets, bracelets, and torcs worked with rune-patterns that
serve as both decoration and spiritual practice.
Adventurers
Half-Giant adventurers are driven by the fundamental tension of their existence: too large for the
human world, too mortal for the Giant legacy, and perpetually searching for a place where their
dual nature is an asset rather than a burden. Fighters, clerics, and druids are the most common
adventuring classes, their physical power and elemental connection making them formidable in
combat and invaluable in wilderness exploration. A Half-Giant in an adventuring party is
impossible to miss and impossible to ignore—they carry the heaviest loads, break down the
sturdiest doors, and draw every eye in every room they enter, a quality that some Half-Giants find
liberating and others find exhausting.
Designer's Note: Half-Giants are a playable race but require DM approval due to their Large size.
Their physical power is offset by social challenges, cramped dungeon corridors, and the difficulty
of finding equipment, mounts, and lodging designed for someone who stands ten feet tall.
