Silentborn
“The children of stolen ancestry --- echoes of forbidden craft.”
Origin & Mythology
The Silentborn are the most tragic race in all of Oreka, and the most controversial. They are
hybrids of Kin and Dómnathar, created not through love or accident but through the Deceivers'
brutal breeding experiments—a systematic program of forced unions, arcane manipulation, and
biological engineering designed to produce tools for the Dómnathar's war against the Kin. They
were never meant to be a people. They were meant to be weapons: infiltrators who could pass
among the Kin undetected, soldiers who combined Kin resilience with Dómnathar cunning,
and—most importantly—test subjects through whom the Deceivers could study Kin-sense, the
elemental resonance that binds the true peoples of Oreka to each other and to the world.
The experiments were conducted in hidden laboratories beneath Dómnathar-controlled territory,
and they were as cruel as anything the Deceivers ever devised. Captured Kin—Elves, Humans,
Dwarves, Halflings—were forced into unions with Dómnathar subjects, their offspring studied,
tested, and discarded when they failed to meet the experimenters' standards. The Silentborn who
survived this process emerged carrying a fractured version of Kin-sense: a null resonance, a
silence where the Song of the World should be. To other Kin, a Silentborn feels wrong—not hostile,
not foreign, but absent, like a gap in a melody, a rest where a note should sound. This absence is
the source of their name and the root of the fear and mistrust that follows them everywhere they
go.
When the Deceivers' War ended, the Silentborn who had survived the laboratories found
themselves in an impossible position: too Kin to live among the Dómnathar remnants, too
Dómnathar-touched to be accepted by the Kin. Many were killed in the aftermath of the war,
caught in the crossfire of a world that had no category for what they were. Those who survived
fled into the margins—outcasts, shadow-walkers, seekers of meaning in a world that regarded
them as abominations. And from these scattered survivors, slowly and in secret, a community
began to form.
The Silent Concord

Chapter 1: Races of Oreka
51
The Silent Concord is the closest thing the Silentborn have to a nation, though it resembles a
secret society more than a government. Founded by first-generation Silentborn survivors in the
decades after the Deceivers' War, the Concord exists to protect its members from exploitation,
oppose Dómnathar remnants who still seek to use them, and establish a Silentborn identity and
culture independent of the horror of their creation. Its organizational structure reflects the
paranoia and secrecy that survival demands:
The Stillwater Council—a circle of elder Silentborn and doctrine keepers—sets broad policy,
guided by the Voice of Stillwater, a singular spokesperson who represents the Concord in the
rare situations where external communication is necessary. Below the Council, the Concord is
organized into Choirs, regional orders divided by function: the Veil Choir handles
counter-infiltration and intelligence; the Hearth Choir maintains hidden refuges; the
Warden Choir** provides combat response; the **Memory Choir
preserves Silentborn history and lore; and the Dawn Choir manages the delicate, dangerous work
of diplomacy with the Kin. At the operational level, the Concord's work is carried out by
Lanterns—local cells of three or more Silentborn who operate autonomously, bound together by
Mirror Oaths: rituals of honesty that require members to reject the Dómnathar practices of
deception, impersonation, and manipulation that created them.
The Concord's core laws are stark and uncompromising. No Binding, No Chains: Silentborn may
not enslave or be enslaved. No Birth Without Choice: the forced creation or breeding of
Silentborn is the Concord's gravest crime. Nothing Done Alone: all operations require triads,
both for safety and to prevent the isolation that makes individuals vulnerable to Dómnathar
manipulation. These laws are not idealistic—they are survival strategies, forged by a people who
know firsthand what happens when autonomy is stripped away.
Society & Traditions
Silentborn rarely form visible settlements. Their communities are hidden: concealed rooms in
larger cities, underground refuges in wilderness areas, and the mobile Lantern cells that serve as
both family units and operational teams. Within these hidden spaces, the Silentborn have
developed a culture built on mutual protection, psychological support, and the constant,
exhausting work of identity formation—the process of building a self that is neither Kin nor
Dómnathar but something new. Mirror Oaths bind Concord members to honesty within the
community, and training programs teach anti-recruitment strategies designed to protect
Silentborn from Dómnathar remnants who still seek to weaponize them.
Silentborn values reflect their origins and their aspirations:
identity beyond creation (the belief that they are more than the experiments that made them),
protection of the Kin from the horrors that created the Silentborn (a commitment that exists
alongside, and often in tension with, the Kin's own fear and rejection of them),
discovery of purpose (a spiritual quest that each Silentborn undertakes individually), and
control over their unnatural abilities (a practical necessity, since untrained Silentborn powers
can manifest unpredictably and dangerously).
Relations

OREKA — Echoes of the Elemental Dawn
52
The Silentborn's relationship with the wider world is defined by three words: feared, hunted,
distrusted. The Kin fear them because Kin-sense reads Silentborn as an absence—a silence that
triggers deep, instinctive unease in peoples who have relied on elemental resonance for their
entire history. Dómnathar remnants hunt them because they are escaped property, failed
experiments, and—worst of all—living evidence of Dómnathar atrocities. And everyone else
distrusts them because no one fully understands what they are, what they can do, or whose side
they are on.
The only reliable protection the Silentborn have is the Silent Concord itself, and even that
protection is fragile. Some Silentborn serve as spies, wardens, or investigators for Kin
communities that are willing to overlook their nature in exchange for their unique
abilities—particularly their capacity to detect Dómnathar activity through their residual
Kin-sense variance. But these arrangements are always precarious, always conditional, and
always shadowed by the knowledge that the Kin community's tolerance could evaporate the
moment the Silentborn's usefulness ends. The Dómnathar's greatest fear is the transformation of a
Silentborn into a True Kin—a metaphysical shift that, if possible, would represent an existential
threat to everything the Deceivers built.
Appearance
Silentborn appearance varies dramatically, reflecting the diverse Kin bloodlines used in their
creation. Many appear as normal members of whatever Kin race contributed their non-Dómnathar
heritage—a Silentborn with human and Dómnathar parents might look entirely human at first
glance. But the Dómnathar influence always shows, especially under stress: eyes that shift to
spectral hues (violet, silver, or an unsettling pale gold), faint Dómnathar features (slightly
elongated ears, an unnervingly graceful posture, skin that seems to absorb rather than reflect
light), and scars or marks of experimentation that many Silentborn carry as permanent
reminders of their creation.
Silentborn clothing tends toward the practical and nondescript. Members of the Silent Concord
favor dark, layered garments that allow them to blend into crowds—grays, deep blues, and
muted browns—with hoods, scarves, or masks available for situations where their features might
betray their nature. The Concord's only visible symbol is the Shattered Mirror—a small pin or
pendant depicting a broken looking-glass—worn only among other Silentborn and hidden from
outsiders.
Magic & Abilities
Silentborn abilities are a direct consequence of their hybrid nature. The collision of Kin elemental
resonance and Dómnathar abyssal silence has produced a unique set of powers that are neither
fully elemental nor fully shadow-based but something disturbingly in between. Minor psionics
manifest as flashes of insight, sudden awareness of others' emotions, and the ability to project
brief mental impressions.
Shadow-attuned abilities allow Silentborn to slip into darkness more easily than their physical
forms should permit, fading from notice in dimly lit spaces with an effectiveness that borders on
supernatural.
Their most distinctive ability is enhanced perception—a residual variant of Kin-sense that has
been warped by Dómnathar influence into something the true Kin cannot replicate. Where a

Chapter 1: Races of Oreka
53
normal Kin individual senses others as notes in the Song of the World, a Silentborn perceives the
gaps—the silences, the discordances, the places where the Song has been disrupted. This makes
them uniquely suited to detecting Dómnathar infiltrators, disguised creatures, and anyone
attempting to conceal their true nature through magical means. It also means that Silentborn
experience the world in a fundamentally different way from every other sentient being in Oreka—a
loneliness so profound that many Silentborn describe it as living inside a song they can hear but
never join.
Adventurers
Silentborn adventurers are among the most compelling and conflicted characters a player can
portray. Driven by the need for purpose, the desire to prove their worth to a world that fears them,
or simply the practical reality that a life on the move is safer than a life in one place, Silentborn
gravitate toward roles that leverage their unique abilities: rogues, rangers, and scouts who use
their shadow-attunement and enhanced perception to protect groups that might otherwise reject
them. Some Silentborn take the more dangerous path of serving as
counter-Dómnathar operatives for the Silent Concord, using their Kin-sense variance to track
Deceiver remnants through the underground networks that still riddle Oreka's foundations.
A Silentborn in an adventuring party is the member no one fully trusts at first—and the one
everyone relies on by the end. Their perception catches what others miss. Their shadow abilities
open paths that others cannot find. And their bone-deep understanding of what it means to be
used, manipulated, and discarded makes them ferociously loyal to companions who treat them as
people rather than tools.
Designer's Note: Silentborn are a playable race but require DM involvement due to their complex
social position. Campaigns featuring Silentborn PCs should engage with themes of identity,
belonging, and the consequences of the Deceivers' War.
