Half-Dómnathar
“Children of two worlds --- neither welcomed, nor fully rejected.”
Origin & Mythology
Half-Dómnathar arise from the collision of Kin and Deceiver bloodlines, and their origins are as
varied as they are painful. Some are the products of infiltration missions, born when Dómnathar
agents assumed false identities and lived among the Kin long enough to produce children. Others
result from forced unions during the Deceivers' War, a brutality that the Kin have never forgiven
and that the Dómnathar regard with clinical indifference. A rare few are the children of
genuine relationships between Dómnathar exiles and Kin individuals—relationships that both
sides consider scandalous and that produce offspring doubly burdened by the stigma of their
parentage. And some are simply the unintended consequences of Dómnathar sabotage operations,
born into a world that has no comfortable place for them.
Unlike the Silentborn, who were deliberately engineered in laboratories, Half-Dómnathar are born
through natural (if often coerced) reproduction. This distinction matters to the Kin, though not
always in the Half-Dómnathar's favor: where Silentborn are pitied as victims of experimentation,
Half-Dómnathar are feared as the children of the enemy—living proof that the Dómnathar walked
among the Kin, wore their faces, shared their beds, and left behind offspring that carry Deceiver
blood in Kin veins. On Kin-sense, a Half-Dómnathar registers as a weak, discordant Kin—a
cracked resonance, a note that sounds almost right but never quite resolves. This is perhaps the
cruelest aspect of their existence: they are close enough to Kin to be recognized, but warped
enough to be distrusted by everyone who recognizes them.

Chapter 1: Races of Oreka
55
Society & Role
Half-Dómnathar exist in three broad categories, depending on which side of the war shaped their
upbringing. Those raised among the Dómnathar serve as elite troops: strike squad leaders,
assassin cell operatives, and troop sergeants embedded in mixed units to enforce discipline
and provide tactical cohesion. The Dómnathar value them as expendable assets—more resilient
than non-Kin slaves, more obedient than full-blooded Dómnathar, and perfectly suited for
operations that require someone who can pass among the Kin without triggering the immediate
revulsion that a pure Dómnathar's total silence on Kin-sense would provoke.
Those raised among the Kin face a different set of challenges. Some are raised by their Kin parent
(usually a mother who did not know her partner's true nature until after the child was born) and
grow up in Kin communities, marked by their discordant resonance and the whispers that follow
them. Others are orphaned or abandoned and find their way to the Silent Concord, where they
are accepted alongside the Silentborn as fellow victims of Dómnathar cruelty. A very few manage
to build lives in tolerant communities—typically Eruskan port cities or Pasua villages, where
outsiders are more readily accepted—but even in these havens, the knowledge of what they are
never fully fades.
The third category is the most dangerous: Half-Dómnathar who have been raised by neither side
and have chosen their own path. These individuals—wanderers, mercenaries, criminals, or
seekers—are unpredictable by nature, shaped by a lifetime of rejection and self-reliance. Some
become threats. Others become heroes. Most simply survive, which is achievement enough for
someone born into a world that wishes they didn't exist.
Appearance
Half-Dómnathar inherit a blend of Kin and Dómnathar features, the proportions varying depending
on parentage. Common Dómnathar traits include slightly elongated ears (more pointed than
even an Elf's),
skin that runs darker than their Kin parent's (ranging from deep olive to dusky gray), and
eyes with a faintly luminous quality in low light—a reflection of the Dómnathar's darkvision
heritage. Their builds tend toward the lean and agile, regardless of which Kin race contributed the
other half of their bloodline, and they move with an
unnervingly graceful poise that many Kin find unsettling.
Half-Dómnathar raised among the Deceivers dress in the dark, functional garb of military
operatives: mithral shirts under dark leather, paired short swords, hand crossbows, and the tools
of infiltration and assassination. Those raised among the Kin dress to blend in, adopting whatever
style is local and adding no distinctive markers that might draw attention. Those who have found
the Silent Concord sometimes adopt the Shattered Mirror symbol alongside the Silentborn, a
gesture of solidarity that not all Silentborn welcome.
Adventurers
Half-Dómnathar adventurers are driven by the same needs that drive all marginalized peoples:
survival, purpose, and the hope of finding companions who judge them by their actions rather than
their blood. Rogues and fighters are the most common classes—the Dómnathar's martial training
runs strong in their descendants, and even those raised among the Kin often gravitate toward

OREKA — Echoes of the Elemental Dawn
56
stealth-based roles that let them operate from the shadows where they feel safest. A
Half-Dómnathar in an adventuring party brings stealth, combat skill, and an intimate
understanding of the Deceivers' tactics—knowledge that can be invaluable when the party
encounters Dómnathar remnants, and deeply uncomfortable when the party realizes exactly how
their companion acquired that knowledge.
Designer's Note: Half-Dómnathar are playable at LA +0, making them accessible as starting
characters. Their social stigma and light sensitivity provide meaningful roleplay challenges
without mechanical disadvantage severe enough to discourage play. DMs should work with
players to establish the character's origin and upbringing, as these factors dramatically shape a
Half-Dómnathar's personality, skills, and relationship with the party.
