Other Peoples & Non-Kin Races

Chapter 1: Races of Oreka
57
This chapter collects all the non-Kin beings of Oreka who possess intelligence, culture, or
recognized societal presence—even if they are not considered "Kin" by the Elemental Lords'
lineage. Some, like the Farborn, are foreign peoples who arrived from beyond Oreka's borders
and have no elemental resonance at all. Others, like the Wargs and Goblins, were brought by the
Deceivers as auxiliaries and servitor races, only to break free and forge their own destinies. Still
others—the Tanuki, River Serpents, and various elemental spirits—are native to Oreka but stand
outside the Kin lineage, created by forest spirits or elemental forces rather than by the Giants and
Elves. On Kin-sense, these peoples register as wild static—present, alive, but fundamentally
different from the elemental resonance of true Kin. This does not make them lesser. It makes them
something the Kin have never fully understood, and in some cases, never fully trusted.
Farborn
"Strangers who chose honor over obedience, and built a home from nothing."
Origin & History
The Farborn are the descendants of the Gilded Standard Company, a mercenary force of
approximately two thousand fighting men and
four thousand camp followers who arrived in Oreka as foreign auxiliaries in the Deceiver
host. They were not Kin. They were not Dómnathar. They were simply soldiers from another
world—predominantly human, with a scattering of half-orcs, half-elves, and a
small cadre of foreign dwarves (all male)—dragged across the planes by promises and threats,
pressed into service in a war they did not understand, and destined for a sacrifice they did not
consent to.
When their commander, Captain Ralven Duskharrow, learned that the Dómnathar intended to
use the Gilded Company as disposable shock troops in a battle designed to kill them, he made the
decision that would define his people for the next three centuries: he refused. The Company broke
away from the Deceiver host in a fighting withdrawal that cost them a third of their number, fled
south across the steppes, and settled in the shadow of a massive solitary mountain known as
the Lone Titan, near the Great Pass. The location was chosen for defense, isolation, trade
access, and—though they did not understand this at the time—metaphysical protection: the Lone
Titan's deep stone roots disrupted Dómnathar scrying, making the Company invisible to the
masters they had betrayed.
Over three hundred years, the Gilded Standard Company transformed from a refugee army into a
mercenary-trader society and finally into a settled, respected non-Kin culture: the Farborn.
Their population grew to approximately twenty-eight thousand. The original foreign dwarves
died out without female descendants, but their cultural and genetic legacy survives in the
Farborn's stockier builds, their reverence for craft, and their stubborn, pragmatic temperament.
The Farborn represent a third category of people in Oreka—neither Kin nor Dómnathar, but
foreign-born natural beings whose presence has slowly begun to interact with Oreka's
elemental metaphysics in ways that no one fully understands.
Society & Traditions

OREKA — Echoes of the Elemental Dawn
58
Farborn society is organized around the Company structure that preserved them during their
earliest and most desperate years. Their government is led by a single leader—the
Captain-General—who holds authority by merit and acclamation rather than hereditary right.
Below the Captain-General, a council of senior officers manages trade, defense, and diplomacy.
There are no nobles among the Farborn except their leader; rank is earned through service, skill,
and the respect of one's peers. This egalitarian military structure has proven remarkably durable,
surviving three centuries of growth and prosperity without producing the feudal hierarchies that
plague most human societies.
The Farborn's defining cultural identity is their horse culture. They brought with them from their
home plane a breed of massive foreign war-steeds unlike anything Oreka had ever
seen—enormous, powerful animals that the Farborn call Titanborne, after the mountain that
sheltered them. Over generations, the Farborn preserved approximately fifty pure Titanborne as
sacred breeding stock (never sold, never traded, displayed only as proof of lineage) while
crossbreeding them with Orekan horses to produce Titanbreed hybrids—animals that combine
the Titanborne's power and courage with the Orekan horse's speed and adaptability.
Approximately nine hundred Titanbreed hybrids now form the backbone of Farborn cavalry,
and a
new Paragon associated with the Titanbreed line has recently emerged—a metaphysical
development that has startled Kin scholars, who did not expect Oreka's elemental forces to
interact with non-Kin bloodlines.
Military Doctrine
The Farborn maintain a standing fighting force of approximately five hundred men-at-arms,
organized into two distinct cavalry traditions. The Wind-Riders are light and medium cavalry
inspired by the mounted skirmishers of the Farborn's ancestral homeland—fast, mobile, and
devastating in hit-and-run engagements, they ride Titanbreed hybrids and fight with composite
longbows, sabers, and lances. The Titan Knights are heavy cavalry, rare and prestigious, who
fight as shock troops in full plate on Titanbreed destriers. The Wind-Riders form the majority of
the Farborn's military strength; the Titan Knights are deployed only in the most critical
engagements, their charges legendary for the sheer weight of horse and steel they bring to bear.
Relations
The Farborn occupy a unique diplomatic position in Oreka: respected but watched, trusted but
never fully embraced. The Kin regard them with a mixture of gratitude (for their betrayal of the
Deceivers), curiosity (for their foreign customs and non-Kin nature), and wariness (because they
arrived with the enemy, and no amount of honor can entirely erase that association). The
Farborn's Neutral Good alignment and their consistent willingness to protect caravans, guard
trade routes, and act as neutral defenders against Deceiver remnants have earned them genuine
goodwill in most Kin communities, particularly among the Eruskan trading cities and the Orean
mountain settlements. Their
Titanbreed horses are coveted trade goods, commanding prices of
eight thousand to fifteen thousand gold pieces depending on age and training, and Farborn
trade caravans are a welcome sight at markets across Oreka.

Chapter 1: Races of Oreka
59
The Farborn's motto, inherited from Captain Ralven himself, captures their ethos perfectly:
\*"Your life is worth more than your master."
Appearance
Farborn are recognizably human but subtly distinct from any of Oreka's four human subraces.
Three centuries of isolation and interbreeding among a relatively small founding population have
produced a distinctive look: medium builds with broader shoulders than most Orekan humans
(the dwarven admixture showing through), tanned or olive skin weathered by steppe winds,
dark hair ranging from deep brown to black, and sharp, watchful eyes in shades of brown,
hazel, or gray. Their faces tend toward strong, angular features—high cheekbones, prominent
jaws, and the slightly flattened noses of people who have spent generations on horseback in high
wind.
Farborn dress reflects their dual identity as warriors and traders. In the field, they wear practical
riding leathers reinforced with metal plates, with the iconic gilded shoulder-clasp (a small gold
pin in the shape of a rearing horse) that marks them as Company descendants. For trade and
diplomacy, they favor layered steppe garments—wool tunics, leather vests, and heavy cloaks—in
earthy tones of brown, gold, and deep red. The most prestigious Farborn carry Titansteel
horseshoes as good-luck tokens, and every Wind-Rider wears a
feather-and-bone charm braided into their horse's mane.
Adventurers
Farborn adventurers are driven by the same restless energy that brought their ancestors across
the planes three centuries ago. Rangers, fighters, and scouts are the most common classes—the
Farborn's cavalry tradition breeds excellent mounted combatants, and their trade-route
experience produces skilled navigators and diplomats. A Farborn in an adventuring party brings
horses, tactical thinking, and a foreigner's perspective on Kin politics that can be both refreshingly
honest and uncomfortably blunt. They are also, to a person, superb riders—a Farborn who cannot
ride is a contradiction in terms, and a Farborn who rides poorly is a social outcast.
Designer's Note: Farborn use the standard Human racial traits from D&D 3.5e with the following
cultural package applied at character creation. They are non-Kin and do not register on Kin-sense
(they read as 'wild static'). Farborn PCs offer unique roleplay opportunities as outsiders navigating
Kin society.
RACIAL TRAITS
Type Humanoid (Human)
Size Medium
Speed 30 ft.
Ability Scores As standard Human: +2 to one ability score of choice
Vision Normal
Languages Automatic: Common, Farborn (a trade pidgin blending their ancestral tongue
with Orekan Common). Bonus: any

