Level Adjustment +0
Hobgoblins
"Disciplined soldiers forged in chains, now fighting for masters or for themselves."
Origin & History
Hobgoblins were brought to Oreka through the Assault Gate as part of the Deceiver host's
auxiliary forces—never-Kin mercenaries and servitor races pressed into service alongside goblins,
orcs, ogres, and gnolls. But where goblins were used as expendable infantry and orcs as shock
troops, hobgoblins served a more specialized role: they were the Deceivers' professional
soldiers, the disciplined backbone of mixed-race formations that would otherwise dissolve into
chaos. Hobgoblin sergeants and captains held goblin mobs together, organized supply lines,
maintained tunnel fortifications, and provided the tactical competence that the Dómnathar's battle
plans required but their arrogance prevented them from developing among their own kind.
This military professionalism is the hobgoblin's defining characteristic and their greatest curse.
Unlike the goblins, who broke free during the
Battle of the Dark Dawn and scattered into dozens of independent tribes, most hobgoblins
remained with the Deceiver remnants after the war—not out of loyalty, but because their entire
social structure was built around command hierarchies, and without a hierarchy to serve, a
hobgoblin is a soldier without an army: dangerous, directionless, and deeply uncomfortable. The
Dómnathar understood this perfectly, and exploited it ruthlessly. To this day, the majority of
hobgoblins in Oreka serve Deceiver remnant factions as garrison troops, tunnel wardens, and
formation fighters, their discipline making them far more dangerous than their individual
strength would suggest.
A minority of hobgoblins, however, have broken free. Some followed the goblins into independence
during the Dark Dawn and its aftermath, forming Iron Tribes—small, tightly organized
communities that maintain hobgoblin military tradition without Dómnathar masters. Others have
drifted into mercenary work, selling their tactical skills to Kin settlements that are willing to
overlook their Deceiver associations in exchange for reliable, disciplined defense. These free

Chapter 1: Races of Oreka
61
hobgoblins are rare, distrusted, and perpetually on the edge of either acceptance or violence—but
they represent something the Dómnathar never intended: hobgoblins who choose their own
commanders.
Society & Culture
Hobgoblin society is rigidly hierarchical and intensely martial. Every hobgoblin knows their
rank, their commanding officer, and their place in the formation. This is not mindless
obedience—hobgoblins are intelligent, pragmatic, and capable of genuine tactical creativity—but
it is a deep cultural imperative that shapes every aspect of their lives. Hobgoblin communities are
organized as companies: permanent military units that serve as both army and family. Within a
company, authority flows from the War-Captain (the highest-ranking officer) down through a
chain of sergeants and squad leaders to the individual soldiers. Disputes are settled by rank; if
rank is equal, by
formal combat governed by strict rules that prevent the kind of chaotic bloodletting that
weakens orc and goblin societies.
Hobgoblin culture values discipline, efficiency, endurance, and loyalty to the unit. Personal
ambition is acceptable—encouraged, even—but only if it strengthens the company rather than
undermining it. A hobgoblin who advances through competence is respected; one who advances
through treachery is executed. This code of conduct, called the Iron Law, predates their arrival in
Oreka and may be the oldest continuous cultural tradition among any of the auxiliary races. Free
hobgoblin Iron Tribes maintain the Iron Law with religious intensity, viewing it as the one thing
that separates them from the goblins and orcs—and, not coincidentally, from the Dómnathar,
whose society runs on institutional betrayal.
Relations
Hobgoblins are feared and distrusted by virtually everyone in Oreka, and not without
reason—the majority still serve Deceiver remnant forces, and even free hobgoblins carry the
cultural scars of centuries of Dómnathar service. The Kin regard them as dangerous enemies or, at
best, unreliable mercenaries. Goblins have a complicated relationship with hobgoblins: they
respect hobgoblin discipline but resent hobgoblin authority, and the memory of hobgoblin
sergeants enforcing Dómnathar orders on goblin infantry has not faded. Wargs despise hobgoblins
almost universally, viewing them as collaborators who chose chains over freedom. The Farborn,
interestingly, are the most tolerant of hobgoblins—perhaps because, as fellow former Deceiver
auxiliaries, they understand the difference between serving a master and choosing a master.
Appearance
Hobgoblins are tall, powerfully built goblinoids standing 5.5 to 6.5 feet tall—significantly
larger than their goblin cousins and comparable in height to most humans. Their skin ranges from
dark orange to reddish-brown, with a rough, leathery texture that speaks of lives spent in armor
and harsh conditions. Their faces are broad and flat, with heavy brows, sharp amber or red
eyes, and
prominent lower canines that jut upward past their upper lips. Their hair, when they have it, is
coarse and dark—usually black or deep brown—and worn short or shaved entirely, both for
practicality under helmets and as a marker of military discipline.

OREKA — Echoes of the Elemental Dawn
62
Hobgoblin dress is almost exclusively military. Even free hobgoblins prefer chainmail, heavy
shields, and well-maintained weapons to civilian clothing. Their armor is practical rather than
decorative, but obsessively maintained—a hobgoblin with rusty armor is a hobgoblin who has lost
all self-respect. Deceiver-aligned hobgoblins often wear
scavenged dwarven gear taken from the ruins of Aldenheim, a practice that infuriates the Kin
and particularly the Vestri Dwarves. Free hobgoblins of the Iron Tribes have begun developing
their own aesthetic:
dark iron worked with angular geometric patterns that echo neither Dómnathar nor Kin design
traditions.
Adventurers
Hobgoblin adventurers are almost always deserters, exiles, or Iron Tribe members who have
broken with Deceiver service. Fighters are by far the most common class—hobgoblin culture
produces excellent warriors—but hobgoblin rangers (specializing in tunnel warfare and tracking)
and the rare hobgoblin cleric (worshipping pragmatic or war-focused deities) also appear. A
hobgoblin in an adventuring party is the member who keeps watch without complaint, maintains
the group's equipment, insists on marching order and watch rotations, and silently judges
everyone else's tactical decisions. They are not easy companions, but they are reliable ones—and
in Oreka, reliability is a virtue that can compensate for a great deal of social stigma.
Designer's Note: Hobgoblins use the standard Monster Manual hobgoblin entry as their racial
base, adapted for Oreka. They are non-Kin auxiliaries and read as 'wild static' on Kin-sense.
Hobgoblin PCs require DM approval and should have a clear reason for breaking with Deceiver
service.
RACIAL TRAITS
