Chapter 1: Races of Oreka
63
Weapon Prof. Proficient with all simple and martial weapons, light and medium armor, and
shields.
Favored Class Fighter
Level Adjustment +1
Wargs
"Intelligent wolf-like warriors whose loyalty must be earned, never commanded."
Origin & Mythology
Wargs originated as a race on the Deceivers' side, brought across the Assault Gate as beasts of
war, living cavalry mounts, and partners to goblin riders in conquest. Their intelligence was
catastrophically underestimated by their Dómnathar masters, who treated them as animals with
useful instincts rather than as the fully sapient beings they are—beings who are, in fact, often
more intelligent than the goblins who rode them. The Deceivers used wargs as expendable
shock troops, attack animals, and terror weapons, chaining them with arcane bindings and
controlling them through pain and starvation.
During the Battle of the Dark Dawn, the spiritual upheaval triggered by Giant's blood and
elemental storms caused a critical shift in many wargs: those who had been hovering on the edge
of full sapience awakened completely, and those who were already sapient found the strength to
act. The resulting revolt—known among wargs as the Great Howl of Freedom—saw thousands of
wargs break their chains, kill their handlers, and flee into the forests and plains of Oreka. This
moment is the founding event of warg culture and is still celebrated with howling ceremonies on
the anniversary of Dark Dawn.
Society & Culture
Warg society is organized into Packs (family or blood-bound groups of ten to thirty individuals),
which gather periodically into Howl Circles (spiritual assemblies) and Moon Councils
(leadership gatherings held during full moons). Authority within a pack is earned through
demonstrated wisdom, courage, and fair judgment—not through size or fighting ability alone,
though physical strength certainly helps. The warg values of loyalty, honor, earned leadership,
respect for elemental spirits, and fierce independence are encoded in an oral tradition of
songs, stories, and proverbs that packs share at Howl Circles, creating a cultural continuity that
spans the scattered warg communities across Oreka.
The relationship between wargs and goblins deserves special emphasis because it is so commonly
misunderstood by the Kin. Goblins ride wargs, yes—but only with the warg's explicit consent,
negotiated between equals. A goblin does not own a warg. A goblin does not command a warg. A
goblin asks, and if the warg agrees, they form a partnership that benefits both: the goblin gains
mobility and a terrifyingly effective combat partner, and the warg gains a rider who can use tools,
open doors, carry supplies, and provide the kind of fine manipulative ability that paws cannot.
Wargbond Tribes—mixed warg-goblin communities built on mutual respect—are among the most
stable and successful non-Kin societies in Oreka.

OREKA — Echoes of the Elemental Dawn
64
Appearance & Abilities
Wargs resemble enormous wolves, standing chest-high to a human with increased shoulder
mass, powerful jaws, and eyes that convey unmistakably humanlike intelligence and emotion.
Their fur ranges from
silver-gray to black, tawny brown, or (rarely) white, and their eyes are amber, gold, or pale
green—colors that glow with an inner light when the warg is emotional or using its elemental
sensitivity. They speak a growling, consonant-heavy language (Warg Cant) that most
humanoids find difficult to reproduce, though some packs have learned Common or Elven for
diplomatic purposes. Their intelligence is extraordinary: wargs are capable of social reasoning,
strategic planning, combat coordination, and—in rare packs—druidic magic drawn from their
deep connection to Oreka's wild places.
Designer's Note: Wargs are available as a playable race with DM permission. Their quadruped
form creates unique gameplay challenges (no hands, cannot use most equipment) balanced by
significant natural abilities. They work best in campaigns that include Wargbond Tribes or mixed
non-Kin communities.
RACIAL TRAITS
