Goblins
“Cunning survivors shaped by oppression and sudden freedom.”
Origin & History

Chapter 1: Races of Oreka
65
Goblins were brought to Oreka as the Deceivers' servitor race—expendable infantry, tunnel
engineers, trap-builders, and general-purpose labor. They were not inherently evil. They were
simply oppressed: small, numerous, clever enough to be useful and weak enough to be controlled,
trapped in a system that valued them only for what they could build and how quickly they could
die. Hobgoblin sergeants enforced discipline. Dómnathar officers gave orders. And goblins dug,
fought, bled, and died in numbers that no one bothered to count.
During the Battle of the Dark Dawn, the warg uprising disrupted the Deceiver command
structure just long enough for the goblins to see their chance. Many rebelled. Some fled. Some
joined the wargs. Others formed
Free Tribes in the forests and hills of central and southern Oreka. The result was the largest
single emancipation event in Orekan history—tens of thousands of goblins suddenly and violently
free, with no infrastructure, no territory, and no allies except the wargs who had broken free
alongside them. What followed was three centuries of adaptation, survival, and the slow, painful
construction of goblin cultures that owed nothing to the Deceivers who had created them.
Society & Culture
Modern goblin societies vary enormously, a direct consequence of the chaotic circumstances of
their liberation. Free Tribes are the most common: egalitarian, clever, and adaptive communities
that prize ingenuity, trickery, and family loyalty above all else. Hill Tribes are more aggressive,
sustaining themselves through raiding and maintaining a deep, justified distrust of all outsiders.
Wargbond Tribes are mixed warg-goblin communities where the two species live as genuine
partners. And Tinker Clans are nomadic groups of goblin engineers and inventors who travel
between settlements, offering their mechanical skills in exchange for food, shelter, and raw
materials. All goblin societies share a core set of values—freedom, ingenuity, trickery, and
family loyalty—and a core set of fears: chains, tunnels, darkness, and the sound of hobgoblin
boots.
Appearance
Goblins are small humanoids standing 3 to 3.5 feet tall, with
large, expressive eyes that dominate their narrow faces and give them excellent vision in low
light. Their skin ranges from green to
gray to mottled brown, depending on regional variation, and their builds are quick, wiry, and
dexterous—built for speed and agility rather than strength. Goblin ears are large and pointed,
their fingers long and nimble, and their teeth sharp enough to serve as weapons of last resort.
Free goblins dress in whatever they can scavenge, trade, or build: patchwork leather, repurposed
cloth, and an astonishing variety of improvised gear that looks terrible and works surprisingly
well.
RACIAL TRAITS
Type Humanoid (Goblinoid)
Size Small (+1 AC, +1 attack, +4 Hide, ×¾ carrying capacity)
Speed 30 ft.

