River Serpents
"Sacred wardens of the Great River, coiling through the waters since the world was young."
River Serpents are ancient creatures of the Great River, created during the Giants' era as
protectors of water routes, guardians of river spirits, and wardens of ancient river
temples. They are large serpentine beings with smooth riverstone scales, intelligent,
expressive eyes, and the capacity to move through water with both grace and terrifying power.
Pekakarlik Dwarves consider River Serpents holy—sacred guardians whose presence in a stretch
of river guarantees the water's purity and the safety of those who travel it with respect. Eruskan
humans incorporate them into boat-blessing rituals, and halfling communities along the Great
River leave offerings of fish and flowers at riverbanks where serpents have been sighted.
River Serpents are not fully sapient in the way that Kin or wargs are, but they possess a deep,
ancient intelligence that responds to elemental resonance and to the emotional state of nearby
creatures. They can distinguish between travelers who mean the river no harm and those who
carry hostile intent, and they react accordingly—with serene indifference to the former and
terrifying aggression toward the latter. Their temperament varies by region: Great River serpents
are generally placid guardians, while serpents in wilder, more remote waterways can be
dangerously territorial.
Storm Wisps

OREKA — Echoes of the Elemental Dawn
68
“Playful but dangerous spirits of the Wind Lord's domain.”
Storm Wisps are elemental spirits of limited sapience that appear in treetops during storms,
manifesting as crackling spheres of blue-white light that dance and spark among the branches.
They are creatures of the Youngest Brother's domain—fragments of wind and lightning given
form and a dim, mischievous awareness. Storm Wisps are curious, reactive, and unpredictable:
they may follow travelers for miles, drawn by the warmth of campfires and the sound of voices,
only to vanish in a flash of static electricity that leaves hair standing on end and metal equipment
uncomfortably warm. Their electric touch can be genuinely dangerous to the unwary, but wisps
rarely attack intentionally—they simply don't understand that what feels like a playful zap to an
elemental spirit feels like a lightning bolt to a mortal.
Hasura Elves incorporate Storm Wisps into their wind-weaving rituals, and Pasua storytellers
regard a wisp sighting as an omen—good or bad depending on the wisp's behavior. Mytroan
nomads leave their tent-flaps open during storms to welcome wisps, believing that a wisp that
enters a tent brings luck to the household.
Sand Wraiths
“The desert's mourning shadows --- echoes of the Giants' passing.”
Sand Wraiths are undead-elemental fusions born from the dying spirits of ancient Giants
and the Infinite Desert's elemental fury. They are not intelligent in any conventional sense, but
they possess a deep, sorrowful awareness—a memory of what the world was before the Giants fell
and the desert consumed their cities. Sand Wraiths manifest as towering humanoid shapes made
of swirling sand and dust, their forms constantly shifting and reforming, their eyes—if they can be
called eyes—glowing with a dim, amber light that is the last trace of the elemental fire that once
burned in Giant hearts.
Sand Wraiths warn trespassers, guard sacred ruins, and represent the sorrow of the Giants'
fall. They are central to desert superstition across Oreka: Mytroan caravans tell stories of wraiths
that led lost travelers to water, and Taraf-Imro smiths speak of wraiths that guard Giant-era forges
containing metals and techniques that have been lost for millennia. Whether Sand Wraiths are
truly the ghosts of Giants, elemental echoes of their passing, or something else entirely is a
question that scholars have debated for centuries and that the wraiths themselves, in their
wordless, howling way, refuse to answer.
Other Spirits & Minor Peoples
Oreka is rich with minor spirits and creatures that fall outside the formal categories of Kin, hybrid,
or auxiliary. Forest Spirits are nature guardians tied to Hasura and Pasua traditions, manifesting
as luminous, half-visible presences in ancient groves. River Spirits are adored by the Eruskan and
courted by halflings, appearing as shimmering figures in waterfalls and rapids. Wind Sylphs,
born of the Youngest Brother's breath, are rare and capricious allies who sometimes befriend
Mytroan wind-callers. Ash Elementals, favored by Rarozhki smiths, are semi-sapient beings of
heat and cinder that dwell in volcanic vents and forge-fires, occasionally offering cryptic guidance
to those who know how to listen. None of these beings are playable races, but all of them shape
the cultural landscape of Oreka in ways that adventurers will encounter, respect, or—at their
peril—ignore.

Chapter 1: Races of Oreka
69
Kin-Sense, Elemental Resonance & Reproductive Rules
This section provides the complete mechanical treatment for three systems that underpin Oreka’s
metaphysics: Kin-sense, the elemental resonance that binds the true peoples of the world to each
other and to the land; Elemental Resonance, the four-element framework that shapes racial
identity, magic, and culture; and the Reproductive Rules that govern what happens when these
systems interact—including the tragic edge cases of the Silentborn. These rules are not optional
flavor. They are the foundation on which Oreka’s identity, conflict, and social structure rest. A DM
who understands Kin-sense understands why the Deceivers were so terrifying, why the Silentborn
are pitied and feared, and why the peoples of Oreka trust each other in ways that peoples of other
worlds simply cannot.
Kin-Sense
Kin-sense is a primal, elemental resonance shared by all true Kin—Giants, Elves, Dwarves,
Halflings, and Humans—and by the Hybrid Peoples who carry Kin blood. It is not a spell, not a
skill, and not something that can be learned or taught. It is ontological: part of what it means to
exist as a being shaped by the Elemental Lords. Kin-sense functions as a subconscious awareness
of belonging, a sympathetic vibration between souls tuned to the same elemental frequency. When
two Kin stand in the same room, they feel each other—not as a visual or auditory phenomenon, but
as a warmth, a rightness, a recognition that the other person belongs to the world in the same
fundamental way they do.
This awareness is not precise in the way that darkvision or tremorsense is precise. Kin-sense does
not reveal identity, alignment, class, level, or intentions. It reveals presence and
nature—specifically, whether a living being resonates with the elemental harmony of Oreka. In
practical terms, Kin-sense tells a character four things: something is there, it is alive, it is Kin
or it is not, and roughly how strong its resonance feels. Everything beyond that requires
normal observation, skill checks, and social interaction.
The Resonance Taxonomy
Every living being in Oreka registers on Kin-sense in one of five ways. Understanding this
taxonomy is essential for DMs, as it drives plot, social encounters, and the horror of the Deceivers.
RACIAL TRAITS
Harmonic Resonance
Warm, sympathetic
vibration. Feels natural
and (Kin)
right. All true Kin—Giants, Elves, Dwarves, Halflings, Humans—register this
way, as do Half-Giants (who register strongly due to their All-Element Concord).
The intensity varies by proximity and emotional state; a Kin individual in
distress resonates more strongly, like a plucked string vibrating harder.
Absolute Silence
Complete absence of
resonance. Feels like a
hole (Void)
in the world—not hostile, not cold, simply nothing where something should be.
All Dómnathar register this way, as do true Deceivers of any race. This is not
merely ’unfamiliar.’ It triggers deep, instinctive unease in Kin who perceive it,
comparable to the primal discomfort of seeing a human face that doesn’t quite
look right. Cannot be hidden, faked, or disguised by any known magic short of
divine intervention.

OREKA — Echoes of the Elemental Dawn
70
Null Resonance Absence
where Kin-resonance
should exist---a gap
(Silent)
in the melody, a rest where a note should sound. Silentborn, Severed (Kin who
have been stripped of resonance through Dómnathar ritual), and Oath-Broken
(Kin who have voluntarily surrendered their resonance) all register this way.
Perceptibly different from Absolute Silence because Null Resonance implies
something was there and was lost, while Absolute Silence implies nothing was
ever there at all.
Wild Static Present and
alive, but fundamentally
different (Non-Kin)
from elemental resonance—like hearing a voice through heavy interference. All
Non-Kin peoples register this way: Farborn, Hobgoblins, Goblins, Wargs, and
most beasts and animals. Wild static does not trigger the instinctive unease of
Silence; it simply reads as ’other.’ Kin can learn to distinguish different types of
wild static with experience (a veteran ranger who has worked alongside Wargs
for years may recognize the specific ’feel’ of Warg static), but this is informal
and unreliable.
Warm Static A faint,
pleasant variant of wild
static that
(Kin-Adjacent)
suggests elemental kinship without full Kin resonance. Tanuki and certain
forest spirits created during the Giants’ era register this way. Kin-adjacent
beings are recognized as ’natural’ and ’belonging’ in a loose sense, but they do
not trigger the full warmth of true Kin-sense.
Kin-Sense Mechanics
Kin-sense is a supernatural ability possessed by all Kin and Half-Kin (Half-Giants, Half-Dómnathar,
Silentborn variant). It functions constantly and passively—no action required, no concentration
needed, no daily uses to track. The following rules govern its use at the table.
Range. Kin-sense functions within 60 feet under normal conditions. This range is reduced to 30
feet in areas of heavy elemental disturbance (volcanic activity, raging storms, proximity to the
Lament of Kings) and extended to 120 feet in areas of deep elemental calm (ancient groves, Giant
ruins in good repair, the interior of a properly maintained Chord Circle). Line of sight is not
required; Kin-sense passes through solid barriers up to 5 feet thick. Barriers of lead, worked
Dómnathar metal, or areas under the effect of False Silence block Kin-sense entirely.
Automatic Detection. Within range, a Kin character automatically detects the presence and
general category (Harmonic, Silent, Void, Wild Static, Warm Static) of any living being. This is not
an action and cannot be suppressed by the Kin character. It simply happens, like peripheral vision.
The character knows something is there and what general category it falls into, but not precise
location, identity, or number (in a crowd, Kin-sense blurs into a general wash of resonance).
Active Concentration. As a move action, a Kin character can focus their Kin-sense on a specific
individual within range. This requires line of sight (or knowledge of the target’s general location)
and reveals the following: the target’s resonance category (confirmed, not just general
impression), the approximate strength of the resonance (strong, normal, weak, flickering), and
whether the target’s resonance is stable or distressed (a Kin individual under duress, magical
compulsion, or emotional extremity resonates differently). This focused use can be opposed: a
target using a magical disguise, polymorph effect, or similar concealment forces a Kin-sense
check (d20 + character level + Wisdom modifier) against the effect’s DC or the disguise check
result.
Kin-Sense vs. Deception. Mundane disguises—wigs, makeup, false accents—do not fool
Kin-sense. A human wearing dwarf armor still registers as a human on Kin-sense. However,
Kin-sense alone does not reveal which human; it merely confirms the person is Kin. Magical

Chapter 1: Races of Oreka
71
disguises and polymorph effects create a temporary false resonance. A Kin character who actively
concentrates (move action) may attempt a Kin-sense check against the spell’s DC or the caster’s
Disguise check to detect the discrepancy. On success, the character perceives the resonance as
’layered’ or ’wrong’ but does not automatically know the true form.
Kin-Sense vs. Silence and Void. The most important application of Kin-sense is detecting
Absolute Silence (Dómnathar and true Deceivers) and Null Resonance (Silentborn and
Severed). No check is required. Any Kin character within range who would otherwise detect a
being automatically perceives the absence. The DM should describe this as a visceral, unsettling
experience—a gap where warmth should be, a silence that feels deliberate and wrong. The horror
of Kin-sense is that it cannot be fooled by Silence: a Dómnathar cannot hide its void by standing in
a crowd of Kin, because the void stands out precisely because everything around it resonates. This
is why the Dómnathar developed False Silence as a weapon—rather than hiding their own void,
they suppress the resonance of everyone around them, creating a zone where nothing registers
and the void becomes invisible against a backdrop of manufactured silence.
Edge Cases & DM Guidance
Crowds. In large gatherings (more than 20 Kin within 60 feet), passive Kin-sense blurs into a
general wash of warmth. Detecting a single Void or Null individual in a crowd requires active
concentration (move action) and a Kin-sense check (DC 15 + 1 per 10 additional people in the
crowd). The Lament of Kings, with thousands of Kin gathered in close proximity, raises this DC to
25 or higher—which is one reason the Dómnathar consider it an ideal operating environment.
Anti-Magic Zones. Kin-sense is supernatural, not magical. An antimagic field suppresses it. A
dispel magic targeted on a Kin character does not suppress their Kin-sense (it is not an active spell
effect), but a dispel magic targeted on an area may create brief ’dead zones’ in the resonance
field, as though a stone had been dropped into still water—ripples of disturbance that last 1d4
rounds before stabilizing.
Undead. Undead creatures do not register on Kin-sense at all. They are simply absent, like
furniture. This is distinct from Void (which feels like an active, deliberate absence) and Null (which
feels like a wound). A vampire who was once Kin registers as nothing; a ghost retains a faint,
flickering echo of its living resonance that a Kin character with active concentration might detect
(DC 20 Kin-sense check). Sentient undead who retain their personality (such as liches) may retain
a corrupted, disturbing echo of their original resonance—a sound like a familiar song played
backwards.
Constructs and Elementals. Constructs do not register on Kin-sense. Pure elementals register
as overwhelming, raw static—a blast of unmodulated elemental energy that is painful to perceive
at close range (within 10 feet, a Kin character must succeed on a DC 15 Will save or be dazzled for
1 round). This is why Kin settlements do not summon unbound elementals casually; to Kin-sense,
an unbound elemental is as uncomfortable as staring directly into the sun.
Sleeping, Unconscious, and Dying Kin. A sleeping Kin individual’s resonance dims but does not
disappear—it becomes slow, rhythmic, like a heartbeat. An unconscious Kin individual’s resonance
becomes erratic and flickering. A dying Kin individual’s resonance flares briefly (detectable at
twice normal range) and then collapses—an event that nearby Kin experience as a sharp, painful
loss, like a string snapping on an instrument. This death-resonance is what makes battlefields so
psychologically devastating for Kin armies: every fallen comrade is felt, not just seen. It is also

OREKA — Echoes of the Elemental Dawn
72
what makes Dómnathar False Silence so insidious—by suppressing the death-resonance of
captives, the Dómnathar can make living prisoners appear dead to everyone who might search for
them.
Elemental Resonance
The four elements—Stone (Earth), Fire, Water (Sea/Ice), and Wind (Air/Sky)—are not merely
physical forces in Oreka. They are the substance of creation, the building blocks from which the
Elemental Lords shaped the world and everything in it. Every Kin race carries an elemental
attunement inherited from the circumstances of their creation, and this attunement shapes their
magic, their temperament, their cultural values, and their relationship to the land.
Racial Elemental Affinities
RACIAL TRAITS
Giants All four elements in equilibrium. Giants are the only Kin who naturally
harmonize with Stone, Fire, Water, and Wind simultaneously—a state called the
All-Element Concord. This is why Giants were the first Kin: they are the most
complete expression of the Elemental Lords’ creative will.
Half-Giants All four elements (inherited). Half-Giants retain the All-Element Concord of
their Giant ancestors, though in a diminished form. Their concord is strong
enough to be mechanically relevant (see the Half-Giant racial entry) but weaker
than a true Giant’s—a chord played on four strings rather than a full orchestra.
Elves Primary: Wind/Air (Youngest Brother’s creation). Secondary: varies by subrace.
Hasura lean toward Wind + Light, Pasua toward Wind + Life, Na’wasua toward
Wind + Stars (a metaphysical variant of Fire/Light), and Kovaka toward Wind +
Earth.
Dwarves Primary: Earth and Fire (Lord of Stone and Lady of Fire’s creation). Secondary:
varies by subrace. Vestri favor Earth, Pekakarlik favor Water (the River Lord’s
adopted children), Rarozhki favor Fire, and Aldenheim (extinct) favored pure
Earth.
Halflings Primary: Water (Lady of the Sea’s creation). Secondary: Life/Growth. Halflings
are the most water-attuned of all Kin, which is reflected in their affinity for
rivers, their cultural emphasis on adaptability and flow, and their racial
Traveler’s Luck (the ability to ’go with the current’ of fate).
Humans Mixed: all elements, with cultural/regional variation. Orians favor Earth,
Eruskans favor Water, Mytroans favor Wind, and Taraf-Imro favor Fire. Humans
are the most elementally flexible of the Kin, able to attune to any element
through training, environment, or devotion. This flexibility is one of the reasons
humans produced the most Ascended Gods—they are less bound to a single
elemental identity and more able to transcend.
Elemental Tolerance (Universal Kin Trait)
All Kin possess Elemental Tolerance, a minor supernatural resistance tied to their primary
elemental affinity. This trait functions as follows: a Kin character gains Resistance 2 against
energy damage associated with their primary element (acid/earth for Stone-attuned, fire for

Chapter 1: Races of Oreka
73
Fire-attuned, cold for Water-attuned, electricity for Wind-attuned). For Kin with mixed attunement
(such as Humans), the character selects one element at character creation; this choice is
permanent and reflects the character’s cultural and spiritual identity. Giants and Half-Giants, with
their All-Element Concord, gain Resistance 2 to all four energy types.
Elemental Tolerance is subtle enough that most Kin do not notice it consciously. A Vestri dwarf
standing in a cold rain does not think ’my earth tolerance is irrelevant here’; she simply endures
and moves on. But in aggregate, across populations and centuries, Elemental Tolerance shapes
where Kin settle, what environments they thrive in, and which elemental hazards they dismiss as
minor inconveniences. It is one reason dwarves build forges deep in volcanic mountains
(fire-attuned dwarves barely notice the ambient heat) and one reason halflings settle near rivers
and coasts (water-attuned halflings shrug off the chill of wet weather that miserable everyone
else).
Elemental Attunement in Magic
A Kin spellcaster casting a spell aligned with their primary element gains a +1 bonus to caster
level for that spell. This bonus applies to duration, range, and effect calculations but not to
damage dice or save DCs. A Rarozhki dwarf wizard casting fireball calculates range and area as
though one caster level higher; the damage remains unchanged. This bonus stacks with other
caster level bonuses (such as those from the Elemental Affinity feat) but is otherwise
unremarkable—it simply reflects the fact that a water-attuned caster manipulating water is
working with the grain of their own nature, not against it.
Conversely, a Kin spellcaster casting a spell opposed to their primary element suffers a -1
penalty to caster level (minimum 1st) for that spell. The opposed elements are Earth/Wind and
Fire/Water. A Mytroan wind-caller casting wall of stone is working against the current of their own
resonance and finds the magic sluggish and resistant. This penalty can be negated by the
Elemental Versatility feat (see Chapter 3: Feats) or by spending a full round action instead of the
spell’s normal casting time, representing the caster’s deliberate effort to force the magic into an
unfamiliar shape.
Reproductive Rules & Cross-Race Offspring
The question of who can produce children with whom is not academic in Oreka. It drives politics,
defines identity, fuels prejudice, and—in the case of the Silentborn—shapes the entire course of
post-war history. The following rules codify what Orekan scholars, healers, and lorekeepers have
documented over thousands of years of observation, and what the Dómnathar discovered through
centuries of brutal experimentation.
Core Principles
Principle 1: Elemental Compatibility. Kin can reproduce with other Kin because they share the
same elemental foundation. The Elemental Lords shaped all Kin from the same four-element
matrix, and this shared origin makes their biology fundamentally compatible regardless of the vast
physical differences between, say, a halfling and a half-giant. This is not genetics in the modern
scientific sense; it is metaphysical resonance. Two beings whose souls vibrate in the same
elemental key can produce offspring whose soul carries a blended chord. Two beings whose souls
vibrate in fundamentally incompatible keys—Kin and Dómnathar, for example—can only produce

OREKA — Echoes of the Elemental Dawn
74
offspring through extreme magical intervention, and the results are always damaged.
Principle 2: Resonance Determines Kinship. A child’s status as Kin is determined by whether
the child’s soul carries elemental resonance. If both parents are Kin, the child is always Kin. If one
parent is Kin and the other is Non-Kin (Farborn, Hobgoblin, etc.), the child has a roughly 50%
chance of being Kin (with diminished but functional resonance) and a 50% chance of being
Non-Kin (registering as wild static). If one parent is Kin and the other is a Void being
(Dómnathar), the child is almost always a Silentborn—a being with null resonance, neither Kin nor
Void but something broken between.
Principle 3: Physical Form Follows the Mother. In cross-race Kin pairings, the child’s physical
form tends to favor the mother’s race, with traits from the father’s race appearing as secondary
characteristics. A child of a human mother and an elven father will be physically human with elven
features (slightly pointed ears, finer bone structure, longer lifespan); a child of an elven mother
and a human father will be physically elven with human robustness (broader shoulders, slightly
shorter ears, faster maturation). Dwarven and halfling crosses with taller races produce children
of intermediate size. Giant crosses are more complex (see Half-Giants, above).
Cross-Race Compatibility Table
