exist through powerful fey magic but have never been documented in Orekan
history.
Silentborn Edge Cases
The Silentborn are the most mechanically and narratively complex reproductive outcome in Oreka,
and DMs should handle them with care. The following edge cases are drawn from canon lore
established in the Silentborn Treatises and from the Dómnathar’s own experimental records
(recovered by the Silent Concord from abandoned laboratories beneath the Lament of Kings).
Can a Silentborn have children? Yes, but the results are unpredictable. A Silentborn who
reproduces with a Kin partner produces a child who is Kin approximately 60% of the
time—higher than the Kin/Non-Kin rate because the Silentborn’s damaged resonance still carries
an echo of elemental origin. The remaining 40% produce children with null resonance
(second-generation Silentborn) or, very rarely, with wild static. A Silentborn who reproduces with
another Silentborn produces a child with null resonance approximately 80% of the time. The
Dómnathar considered this a design failure: they wanted to breed a self-sustaining population of
infiltrators, but the null resonance proved too unstable to reliably propagate.
Can a Silentborn become True Kin? This is the single most dangerous question in Orekan
metaphysics. The Dómnathar believe the answer is no—that Silentborn are permanently severed
from the Song of the World and can never fully rejoin it. The Silent Concord believes the answer is
maybe—that through a combination of powerful elemental magic, willing sacrifice, and a
Silentborn’s own determination, the null resonance might be ’filled’ with borrowed elemental
harmony, transforming the Silentborn into a fully resonant Kin. No confirmed case has ever been
documented. But the Dómnathar fear the possibility enough to make the elimination of ’rogue’
Silentborn a strategic priority—because if even one Silentborn achieves True Kin status, it would
prove that the Deceivers’ greatest weapon—Silence—can be undone.
What about Severed Kin? A Kin individual who has been ritually stripped of their resonance by
Dómnathar magic (a process called Severing) can potentially be restored through the
Reharmonize rite—a Giant-era ceremony that requires a Chord Circle, at least four Kin
participants representing all four elements, and a willing subject. The rite has a base success rate
of approximately 50%, modified by the subject’s Wisdom modifier and the time elapsed since
Severing (+5% per point of Wisdom modifier, -10% per year since Severing). A Severed Kin who is
not restored within a decade is generally considered permanently lost. The Reharmonize rite does
not work on Silentborn (whose resonance was never whole to begin with) or on Oath-Broken (who
surrendered their resonance willingly and must reclaim it through personal transformation, not
external magic).
Kin-Sense, Resonance & the DM\'s Toolkit
The rules above are guidelines, not absolutes. Kin-sense is deliberately designed to be a narrative
tool as much as a mechanical one. The DM should use Kin-sense to create atmosphere, drive social
encounters, and make the Deceivers’ threat visceral and personal. When a PC walks into a room
and feels the warmth of twenty Kin souls and one gap where warmth should be, that is not a skill

OREKA — Echoes of the Elemental Dawn
76
check—it is the moment the adventure begins. When a PC holds a dying friend and feels the
resonance flare and then snap, that is not a mechanic—it is the reason the PC swears revenge.
At the same time, Kin-sense should never be a perfect solution. It reveals presence and nature, not
identity or intent. A Void reading tells you that someone in the room is a Dómnathar or has been
touched by the Abyss Circle; it does not tell you which person, or whether they are a spy, a
refugee, or a prisoner. The best Oreka campaigns use Kin-sense to raise questions, not answer
them. Let the players feel the absence. Let them argue about what it means. Let them be wrong.
That is where the story lives.
